description:
1. "THE GALLERY OF PUBLIC HEROES" (Batman) after getting a new face an escaped con creates a rouges gallery of detectives, plain-clothed cops, insurance investigators, and the like, charging a fee for gangsters to use it.
  2. "ROBOTMAN IN THE MOON" (Robotman)
  3. "THE SINISTER SNOWMAN" (Slam Bradly)
  4. SHORTY
  5. "SECRET CODES IN SPORTS" (text by Henry Lysing)
  6. DAFFY & DOODLE
  7. "FIND ME THE KILLER" (Boy Commandoes)
  8. JERRY THE JITTERBUG

"CRIME'S PUZZLE CONTEST" (Batman) the Riddler returns and gives the public clues to a puzzle contest to provide distractions for his crimes.

"THE FARMER IN THE TILL" (Slam Bradly)

"ROBOT BANDIT" (Robotman)

JERRY THE JITTERBUG

"WHEN YOU CLOSE YOUR MIND" (text story)

"THE MYSTERY OF SECRET X" (Boy Commandoes)

description:
1. "THE EXPERIMENT OF PROFESOR ZERO" (Batman) Batman and Robin recall a case where a mad scientist shrank them.
  2. "THE METAL MAN'S SPORTSATHON" (Robotman)
  3. "A BICYCLE BUILT FOR SLEUTHS" (Slam Bradly)
  4. SARGE (humor strip)
  5. "A POLICEMEN'S LOT" (text story by Lee Goldsmith)
  6. CASEY THE COP (humor strip)
  7. JERRY THE JITTERBUG (humor strip)
  8. "THE KING OF THE ANIMALS" (Boy Commandoes)

description:
1. "THE GHOST OF GOTHAM CITY" (Batman) A clever doctor uses a phony "ghost" of executed mobster Rifle Rafferty and a group of stool pigeons within Gotham City's mobs in order to convince the Police and the Dynamic Duo that Rafferty has come back from the dead to exact revenge.
  2. "ROBOTMAN MEETS ROBOTCROOK" (Robotman)
  3. JERRY THE JITTERBUG (humor strip)
  4. "A DAY IN THE LIFE OF A PRIVATE EYE" (Slam Bradley)
  5. CASEY THE COP (humor strip)
  6. "THE BOY CONQUEROR" (text story)
  7. "AROUND THE WORLD OR BUST" (Boy Commandoes)

description:
1. "I.O.U. MY LIFE" (Batman) a man saves 2 people's lives and has then sign notes that read "I.O.U. my life" then does the same to Batman. several days later he calls them to the museum and threatens they will die in the same manner he saved them from if they don't give him $50,000 each.
  2. "AROUND THE WORLD IN 24 HOURS" (Robotman) a scientist puts a new atomic motor in Robotman against his will and it puts him in overdrive so he runs at super-speed and can't stop, running around the world.
  3. "RICH MAN, PORE MAN, LAWYER MAN...THIEF" (Slam Bradley)
  4. "PHOTOGRAPHY - A MODERN MERICLE" (text story)
  5. BEBE (humor strip)
  6. "THE ORIGIN OF POW-WOW SMITH" (Pow-Wow Smith)

description:
1. "THE FLYING BATMAN": (Batman) Bruce and Dick attend a lecture by a bat expert talking about making bat-like wings for humans they spot a fugitive they had been hunting in the crowd. a quick change and the duo move to apprehend the crook but a stray bullet cuts Batman's rope and he falls, getting knocked out. he dreams that the bat expert's wings work and Batman gets wings.
  2. CAPTAIN TOOTSIE: (Tootsie Roll add)
  3. "THE SECOND ROBOTMAN": (Robotman)
  4. "THE LAND OF LOST YEARS": (Impossible -- But True) a new feature introduced in this issue about Roy Ramond, the hoast of a TV show that shares its name with this feature. in this first story, he treks to a valley where men are said to age years in minutes.
  5. SHORTY: (humor strip)
  6. "VOLCANO SLEUTHS": (text story)
  7. "THE REVENGE OF LITTLE THUNDERCLOUD": (Pow-Wow Smith)

description:
1. "THE UNDERGROUND RAILROAD OF CRIME": (Batman) Batman goes undercover in the state prison to catch a gang that has been breaking out cons with unrecovered loot and smuggling them out of the country in exchange for half the loot.
  2. "THE RIDDLE OF THE RUBY": (Impossible But True) on his search for oddities Roy Raymond is in London when a seemingly dying man gives him an imitation ruby that he claims is cursed.
  3. "ROBOTMAN - MIND READER": (Robotman) strange rays are accidentally emitted from a lab causing Robotman with his metal skull to uncontrollably read the minds of those around him.
  4. SHORTY: (humor strip)
  5. "SCIENCE IS CHAMP": (text article)
  6. "DEATH IN THE NORTHWOODS": (Pow-Wow Smith) while attending a college reunion smith becomes worried about a classmate named Kyle Delaney and insists on accompanying him home to his family's Northwoods lumber camp. there he finds some fugitives have tricked Kyle's sister into thinking she killed someone and are blackmailing her into letting them hideout at the camp.

description:
1. "BRUCE WAYNE PRIVATE DETECTIVE": (Batman) after telling Vikcky that Batman is nothing but a glorified detective and he could probably do the same given the chance she has him fill in for a private detective friend of her while he is in the hospital for a few weeks. he has been doing well when 2 separate clients try to hire him to get a model train that was featured in some pics Vicky took of the Batcave trophy room from batman.
  2. "MIGHTY MARO--THE MAN WHO COULD READ MINDES!": (Impossible But True)
  3. "THE ANDREWS RAIDERS": (special feature) a group of men steels a confederate supply train in Georgia during the civil war and head north, wrecking track and cutting telegraph lines behind them. they are stopped in the end but their actions earn them the first-ever Congressional Metals of Honor.
  4. "LONE WOLF!": the story of LT. Amos Andrews, a motorcycle cop on the Boston post road.
  5. "DANGEROUS BUSINESS": (text story)
  6. JERRY THE JITTERBUG: (humor strip)
  7. CASEY THE COP: (humor strip)
  8. "THE RANGER FROM THE RED DEER VALLY": (Pow-Wow Smith) when a friend of his is killed Smith tracks the killer to Texas and works with theTexas Rangers to catch him.
name: Bruce Wayne, Private Detective

description:
1. "THE BATMOBILE OF 1950": (Batman) after a bad crash wrecks the Batmobile and breaks Batman's leg he uses the time he is laid up to design a new Batmobile.
  2. "THE BEAUTY WHO TALKED WITH BEASTS": (Impossible But True) hunters in Africa return with a wild girl who seems to be able to talk to animals. this is a problem for a man who murdered someone with a dog as the only witness.
  3. TON O FUN: (gag strip)
  4. "TO ARMS": (Robotman)
  5. VARSITY VIC: (gag strip)
  6. "TV QUIZ": (text article)
  7. "THE GREAT GOLD ROBBERY": (Pow-Wow Smith)

description:
1. "THE RACE OF THE CENTURY": (Batman) Batman and Robin are in Canada helping the mounties catch the masked highwayman. he kills a mountie but they can't convict him of the murder because they can't find the bullet. Robin finds the highwaymen's horse and the mounties tell him to keep it but it's terrified of him. the highwayman escapes and tries to kill the horse and they figure out the bullet from the killed mountie is in the horse's neck and it's scared of Robin because the highwayman wears the same kind of mask.
  2. "THE MAN WHO COULD SEE TOMORROW": (Impossible But True) a professor claims to have a machine that can see the future.
  3. THE LITTLE MAYOR: (gag strip)
  4. "POUNDS OF PERIL": (Robotman)
  5. GALLOPING GHOSTS: (western story)
  6. "WITH DRUMS, FIRE, & FLASHES": (text article)
  7. JERRY THE JITTERBUG: (gag strip)
  8. "THE PROMISE OF POW-WOW SMITH": (Pow-Wow Smith)
name: The Race of the Century

description:
1. "THE THOUSAND AND ONE TROPHIES OF BATMAN": (Batman) a criminal hides in a mummy case so batman and robin will take him to their trophy room and uses the trophies to try and kill them.
  2. "THE IMPOSSIBLE MURDERS CASE": (Impossible But True) the mystery of a rocket that goes up empty and comes down with a dead body.
  3. "FELONY AND FUN": (Robotman)
  4. "CLUE CRAZY": (Dover and Clover)
  5. "WINNER TAKE ALL NO 2": (text article)
  6. LITTLE PETE: (humor strip)
  7. "THE BRAVE WHO WAS A COWARD": (Pow-Wow Smith)
name: The 1,001 Trophies of Batman

description:
1. "BRUSE WAYNE - YOU ARE BATMAN!": (Batman) once again a crime boss figures out that Bruce is Batman, this time because batman stopped a robbery on a yacht party, the boss looks at the guest list and finds only 6 men physically capable of being Batman with children the right age to be Robin. he has his men tail the suspects while he stages a crime and only Wayne is unaccounted for when Batman shows up.
  2. "THE CASE OF THE HUMAN DOLLS": (Impossible But True) Roy investigates when an actress, a ballplayer, and a writer all seem to shrink down to six inches tall.
  3. "THE STRONGEST SCOUNDREL ON EARTH": (Robotman)
  4. "HOME SWEET HOME": (Leave It To Blinky)
  5. "UP TO YOUR ELBOWS IN FUN": (text article)
  6. SHORTY: (humor strip)
  7. "CRIME AMOUNG THE CLIFF-DWELLERS": (Pow-Wow Smith)
name: Bruce Wayne - You Are Batman

description:
1. "THE GLOBE-TROTTER OF CRIME": (Batman) Batman and Robin are late to law enforcement convention in their honor so while they wait Gordan, a rep from Scotland Yard, and a rep from the French Surete, in turn, tells the tale of how Batman and Robin were called to London to catch a bad actor who spent fortune funding a world tour for his theater troop that sold almost no seats and napped when he was refused a loan to keep the failed company going. after evading Batman he crosses the channel to France and is finally caught atop the Eiffel tower.
  2. "THE CHAIR THAT TOLD THE FUTURE": (Impossible But True) interest is spreading in an oracle, an empty chair that will answer any question for $100 and seems to never be wrong. on live TV Roy accepts a challenge to prove it is a fake.
  3. "THE RENEGADE ROBOT": (Robotman) a recently released criminal scientist immobilizes Robotman and messes with his inner workings to make him help in his gang's crimes.
  4. "THEY KNOW WHO YOU ARE": (text article)
  5. "THE FLYING INDIANS": (Pow-Wow Smith) during world war 2 Pow-Wow was part of an all-native American flight crew called the flying Indians. the other three surviving members have started a private airport by the same name and Pow-Wow goes to visit them. after getting in traditional garb to fly back to red deer valley for a harvest ceremony the plane is hijacked by smugglers who are on the run from the cops and they are forced to fly them to South America.

description:
note: while a bat-cycle is seen on the cover it is not seen in the Batman story within, though the Batmobile and Batplane are.

  1. "THE MEN WHO DIED ON TIME": (Batman) when a man gets a note that he will die at midnight he laughs it off but at the stroke of midnight he dies in a room full of people and he is just the first to get such a note.
  2. "THE HUMAN SUPER WEAPON": (Impossible But True) a man calling himself Mr. Mind claims to have the power of mind over matter.
  3. DAFFY & DOODLE: (humor strip) Doodle tells Daffy he will meet him halfway and forgive half of the 10$ he owes him. Daffy tells him he'll meet him halfway too and forget the other half.
  4. "DIAMOND KEY TO DOOM": (Robotman) Robotman pursues a diamond thief called Slippery Sam into a cave and when Sam throws the diamonds against the cave wall it creates a tone that shuts Robotman down briefly and he has a dream of going back in time to a medieval court.
  5. LITTLE PETE: (humor strip) Pete gets new skates and falls on his butt, exclaiming the sidewalk is hard. then another kid sees Pete on the grass, telling him he can't skate on grass and Pete responds that he knew but it's nice and soft when he falls down.
  6. "A BUSINESSMAN'S BEST FRIEND": (text article) article about the IRS not counting pats as dependents despite how much pet owners spend on them (something that is still true today).
  7. CASEY THE COP: (humor strip) a kid asks Casey if he is a law officer and supposed to protect people. when he seas sure the kid shows him a report card with 2 Ds and 2 Fs and tells him he better come home with him because he's going to need protection.
  8. "TWO DETECTIVES NAMES SMITH": (Pow-Wow Smith) a detective named Bart Smith pursues jewel thieves from an unspecified east coast big city to Red Deer Valley in Wyoming, where he works with Pow-Wow Smith to catch them.
name: The Men Who Died on Time

description:
1. "THE LAW OF THE IRON ROAD": (Batman) Batman decides it's time for Robin to learn how the railroad police work so he arranges for them to shadow an agent of the railroad protective association.
  2. CASEY THE COP: (humor strip) Casey is assigned to find a lost dog and comes back saying he closed the case. he is asked if he found the dog and in the next panel he answers that the dog found him as we see it bit his leg.
  3. "THE VALLEY OF GIANT INSECTS": (Impossible But True) Roy goes to the Brazilian jungle with a man who claims to have found a village of giant insects.
  4. CHIP: (humor strip)
  5. "THE DISJOINTED ROBOTMAN": (Robotman)
  6. "WHY YOU ARE YOU": (text article)
  7. SHORTY: (humor strip)
  8. TON O' FUN: (humor strip)
  9. "COWBOYS AND INDIANS": (Pow-Wow Smith) while in a town looking for some fugitives Smith overhears a boy saying his dad told him the Indians never win against cowboys.
  10. TON O' FUN: (humor strip)
name: The Law of the Iron Road

description:
1. THE MAN WHO FEARED METAL: (Batman) after being caught in an explosion a criminal gets a small piece of magnetic metal lodged in his head so if he comes within 10 feet of any metal it will move and cause him pain, potentially killing him. to show Batman what it feels like he captures Batman and Robin then fixes a bomb to Batman's neck that will detonate if it comes too close to any metal and gives him 3 hours to get across town to save Robin.
  2. THE ANTI-GRAVITY MAN: (Impossible But True) a man comes on the show claiming to be able to fly after taking some pills and he seems to do it but it turns out to be a trick played in an effort to catch a certain criminal.
  3. SHORTY (humor strip)
  4. ROBOTMAN MEETS ROBOTROBBER: (Robotman)
  5. NO KIDDING: (Dover and clover)
  6. TRAVELS OF A DIMOND: (text article)
  7. PEG (humor strip)
  8. AS LONG AS THE GRASS SHALL GROW: (Pow-Wow Smith) a treaty grants Red Deer Vally to the Sioux tribe for as long as the grass shall grow so a man who wants to steal the land tries to get the grass to stop growing so the tribe will move.
name: The Man Who Feared Metal

description:
1. UNTOLD TALES OF THE BAT-SIGNAL: (Batman) the editor of the Gotham Gazette decides he wants to run a feature story series about the Bat-signal so he assigns a reporter named Dave Purdy to find stories of how it changed people's lives with the big goal being to find a story where the signal alone saved someone. first James Gordon tells of a time when the Bat-signal was mounted on a police boat and pointed into the water it lit all the way to the bottom of Gotham harbor so Batman could see to save a trapped cop. next, Vicki Vale tells how she was kidnapped when she found crooks stealing the Bat-signal but she tricked them into letting her use the signal to dry clothes, and as she moved the clothes the sun reflected off it sent out a flash signal that alerted Batman. finally, Dave talks to Batman and Robin who tell him how after some hoods took a pot shot at the first Bat-signal so it couldn't be used to call Batman they made a new one with bulletproof glass and a super bright light that cuts through fog but on their way to deliver it to GCPD headquarters they got a call about boy scouts trapped in a forest fire. rescuers couldn't find them in the smoke but the new Bat-signal's light cut through the smoke to lead them to safety. they also tell him of a time putting a different slide on the Bat-signal allowed them to show the entire city a picture of a criminal called Killer Craig and how they put an infra-red filter on the Bat-signal so it could be used without being seen by the naked eye during WW2 blackouts. The next day the Bat-signal is on display at a hall of scientific marvels. after hours an escaped criminal comes in shooting. Batman and Dave hide behind the Bat-signal but Batman was hit. Dave waits for the con to get close then blinds him with the signal before knocking him out and this becomes the first story in the series.
  2. THE CASE OF THE TALKING DEAD: (Impossible But True) a woman claims to be able to speak to the dead.
  3. PEG: (humor strip)
  4. THE ROBOT-MOBILE: (Robotman) Robotman uses new jet-propelled skates and a metal donut that holds an entire crime lab on his waist to catch some clever bank robbers.
  5. BONNY: (humor strip)
  6. THE LADY WITH A GUN: (text article about Annie Oakley)
  7. CASEY THE COP: (humor strip)
  8. SCHOOL CHILDREN ROUND THE WORLD: (Superman PSA)
  9. THE WARRIORS IN WAMPUM: (Pow-Wow Smith)
  10. SHORTY: (humor strip)
name: Untold Tales of the Bat-Signal

description:
1. THE STRANGE COSTUMES OF BATMAN: (Batman) Batman and Robin are doing a regular inspection of their crime-fighting equipment including specialized Bat-suits. we see a white suit used for snow, a gold suit used to look like a gold statue, a super-thin cellophane suit that was hidden in Bruce's boot heal when he went undercover in prison, a glow in the dark suit, a spacesuit, and a suit with a bird on the chest that they say is only for the worst emergency. as they battle the one-off villain for this story we see Batman use a fireproof asbestos suit, a glider wingsuit, and a scuba suit. Batman is then shot badly and needs time to recover but shows up the next day in the suit with the bird on its chest and is able to ignore the knockout gas the criminals are using. turns out the suit was built up with foam rubber to let Robin look like Batman and had a built-in respirator.
  2. THE MAN WHO NEVER SLEPT: (Impossible but true) a man claims to have invented a helmet that will let him never need to sleep again.
  3. ONE-MAN FIRE DEPARTMENT: (Robotman) a gang of arsonists take advantage when the city's firefighters go on holiday for the day and Robotman must stop them while doing the job of the entire fire department.
  4. SHORTY: (humor strip)
  5. CABBAGES AND KALE: (Dover and Clover)
  6. LET 'EM EAT WOOD: (text story)
  7. THE RIDDLE OF FORT BRAVE: (Pow-Wow Smith)
  8. NATURE LOVES A NATURE LOVER: (Buzzy)
name: The Strange Costumes of Batman

description:
1. "THE MAN WITH A MILLION FACES!": (Batman) a circus is in town and one of its star attractions is John Gillen, the man with a million faces, a disguise artist who never shows his real face and can make himself look like anyone quickly. Gillen happens to be an old friend of Dick's parents so he introduces Bruce to him after the show.

hours later a famed actor named Hubert Harper draws a crowd just by walking down the street, causing a distraction that allows 2 thieves to rob a jewelry store. this isn't the first such crime but when asked Harper claims he was at home giving a party at the time. naturally, Batman suspects Gillen, who admits to impersonating Harper but claims to have no knowledge of the robbery. he tells them several times someone has left notes on his dresser telling him to impersonate certain people at certain places and times or they will reveal the secret he now trusts Batman with. the reason he hides his face is that he is an ex-con and didn't think the circus would hire him if they knew.

worried the police would never believe his innocence if they found out about his connection Gillen runs before Batman can stop him. in order to catch the thieves and keep them from revealing the secret Batman takes Gillion's place in the circus while Dick signs on as an acrobat.

soon, at the thieves' instruction, Batman is walking near Gotham museum as the governor, distracting the patrolmen with his presence. surmising the thieves were already in the museum Batman and Robin enter and catch them in the act but it is too dark to tell who they are and they use a gun that shoots white flour to get away and then evade the cops in stollen guard's uniforms. Later the dynamic duo finds that gun in the prop tent at the circus, cleaned or fingerprints so it could have been used by anyone.

The next day "Gillen" is ordered to appear at the airport as a famous flyer named Marty Mallen but Batman arranges for the real Mallen to be there so he and Robin can focus on keeping an eye out for trouble. they see a jewel courier being forced into a car. our heroes give chase but the thieves jump from their car, forcing Batman to save the cursor from crashing while they get away.

thinking Gillen tipped Batman off the thieves caused a wall of his tent to fall, revealing Batman. Batman puts on a show to convince people he is just Gillen in disguise with the young acrobat impersonating Robin. during the act, the thieves shoot a rope Robin is balanced on with a flat arrow that cuts it. Batman acts fast to save him but is able to secure a line to himself in the process, convincing people he isn't really Batman. the thieves are caught with the gun that fired the arrow and tricked into revealing that the jewels were hidden in plain sight, replacing fake jewels in circus decorations with real ones.

Gillen is still worried he will be fired if the circus finds out about his past but Batman urges him to come clean so he does and is accepted.

2. CASEY THE COP: (humor strip) Casey is lamenting being assigned to walk the park on such a cold day when he sees something and yells "hey you - wait right there." the man pretests "but officer - I have a license - see?" Casey responds "who's interested in that? I just want to stand here and keep warm." as we see the man is selling hot peanuts.

3. "THE MACHINE FROM WHICH NO MAN CAN HIDE": (Impossible But True) a man claims to have a machine that can find anyone's location with just something they owned. the man arrives at Roy's office just after he received a telagram so humoring him he asks where the telegram was sent from and is correctly told Mexico City. after this Roy decided to give the machine a chance and schedules it on his show.

army intelligence is interested in the machine and wants to test it by giving Roy a compass belonging to a certain officer and not telling him where that officer is but after a millionaire is abducted his wife asks the machine be used to find her husbend. it's agreed and the man with the machine leads the police to the millionaire but it turns out Roy suspected it was a hox and had already frond the man and taken his place, tricking the man with the machine into admitting it was all faked so he could get a reward for finding the millonare.

4. "THE ROBOT ROBORIES": (Robotman) someone is committing crimes with machines from the same company Robotman gets parts for his own body from.

5. YOUR UNITED NATIONS AT WORK: (A Story From The Files Of The World Health Organization)

6. "OF SAILING SHIPS AND WAX": (tex story)

7. LITTLE PETE: (humor strip) Pete is splashing in a puddle when his mom tells him not to get his feet wet. she then tells him to come in and take a bath. a moment later she asks where he is going with his rubbers on and he responds "into the bath! you told me not to get my feet wet didn't you?"

8. "THE INDIAN WHO HAD TO GET RICH": (Pow-Wow Smith) Smith gets a letter from his old school that they want to build a new science building so they are asking alumni for contributions and still need $100,000 in the next 10 days.. he agrees to get the money somehow. he gets $35,000 from the ransom on 3 fugitives, $20,000 from helping a rancher get his cattle to market, another $20,000 in prize money from a rodeo, and the rest from selling a wampum belt.

description:
1. Batman -- Boss Of The Big House: (Batman) in the Batcave, Batman analyzes a photo that proves a man who is about to be executed is innocent. the phone lines are down because of a storm so the dynamic duo race to the prison in the Batmobile, making it just in time. Batman notices the warden is hiding that he is nearly blind and agrees to fill in until a replacement can be appointed. he tells an inmate named Tolmar that his parole came through and he will be released in the morning but that night Tolmar breaks out of his cell and takes a guard hostage to break into the warden's office and get into the records of executed prisoners before surrendering. the next day Tolmar gets his hand stuck in a machine and is sent to the prison hospital but it looks like the injury was deliberate. wanting to get close enough to find out what Tolmar is up to without him knowing, Batman goes undercover as an inmate and gets himself assigned to work in the hospital. he sees Tolmar washing something off the leg of his cot but is then jumped by the prison barber who figured out he was Batman because he had a graze mark on his arm where batman had been shot when Tolmar broke into the warden's office. to convince everyone he isn't Batman he stages an incident where under the influence of a drug that was being tested on him he breaks out and appears to be stopped by Batman. getting back to the hospital he finds out a death row inmate has asked to see Tolmar as his last request. Batman comes in just after Tolmar has found what he was looking for and stops him from whipping it away. turns out the executed man whose file Tolmar had checked stole $250,000 that was never recovered and Tolmar was in his old cell where he had written the state he hit the loot in. the city was on the cot in the prison hospital and the address was on the wall behind the bed in his death row cell. Tolmar hadn't wanted to be paroled because he needed more time to find the city and address.
  2. The Man Who Could Live Under Water: (Impossible But True) a man claims to have a medical condition that keeps him from getting oxygen from the air so he must breathe water.
  3. Buzzy Sores One For The Handicapped: (PSA)
  4. The Case Of The Broken Ski: (A Case Book Mystery)
  5. Robotman, Actor: (Robotman) after some crooks mistake a robot made for a play as Robotman and shoot it up the real Robotman steps in to replace it in the play.
  6. Every Home A Theater: (text story)
  7. The Big Pow-Wow: (Pow-Wow Smith)

description:
1. The Flying Dutchman II: (Batman) while fighting a pirate sub Batman and Robin end up adrift at sea. they are picked up by an old-time sailing ship called The Flying Dutchman II which turns out to be crewed by escaped cons who can't set foot on land because they are only safe from the law as long as they stay in international waters, at least 3 miles from shore.
  2. Shorty: (humor strip)
  3. The Ship That Defied Time: (Impossible But True) Roy investigates the claim that a freight ship called the comet can cross the Atlantic in less than 2 days, a feat that at the time took the fastest passenger ships at least 4 days and most freighters weeks.
  4. Casey The Cop: (humor strip by Henry Boltinoff)
  5. The Racing Robot Car: (Robotman)
  6. Captain Tootsie In The North Woods: (tootsie roll add)
  7. New Tool For Medical Science: (text story)
  8. Casey The Cop: (humor strip by Henry Boltinoff)
  9. The Sherif Who Was Blind: (Pow-Wow Smith) while chasing some fugitives Smith gets a head injury and is temporarily blinded but doesn't let that stop him from catching his quarry.
name: The Flying Dutchman II

description:
1. The Menace Of The Giant Birds: (Batman) Penguin once again gets out of prison and claims to be going straight. he builds a bird sanctuary with giant nests, birdhouses, and bird models while returning things he has stolen. turns out that while returning the stolen object he was planting gas bombs and when they all go off he uses the giant birds which are actually autogyros to raid each place.
  2. Danger In The Deep: (Royal Crown Soda add)
  3. Varsity Vic: (humor strip by Henry Boltinoff)
  4. The Amazing Mr. Planet: (Impossible But True) a strange blue man is found at the base of mount Everest and believed to be an alien.
  5. Quick Quiz: (4 panels of questions and answers)
  6. The Powerless Robot: (Robotman)
  7. Casey The Cop: (humor strip by Henry Boltinoff)
  8. Get It Off Your Chest: (PSA with Buzzy Brown)
  9. Black And Blue: (Dover and Clover)
  10. The Table Top Battlefield: (text story)
  11. Indian Posse: (Pow-Wow Smith)

description:
1. The Outlaw Who Had Nine Lives: (Batman) a man keeps publicly dying and then showing up alive, calling himself the man with nine lives. he is actually a magician doing this to pump up his career but when his gangster brother hears about this he forces him to use his tricks for crime. in the end, he jumps out a window trying to escape Batman and is killed when his head bashes into a wall.
  2. Three Clues To Crime: (Robotman)
  3. The Human Clock: (Impossible - But True)
  4. Emergency Landing: (Captain Tootsie)
  5. Jerry The Jitterbug: (humor strip by Henry Boltinoff)
  6. New Hope For The Convict: (text story)
  7. Peg: (humor strip by Henry Boltinoff)
  8. Casey The Cop: (humor strip by Henry Boltinoff)
  9. The Phantom Brave: (Pow-Wow Smith)
  10. Quick Quiz: (4 panels of questions and answers)
  11. Know Your Country: (PSA with Superboy)

description:
1. Batman's Double: (Batman) Killer Moth escapes from prison but with his identity as Cameron Van Cleer exposed he needs a new front if he is to resume his activities as Killer Moth. rather than set up a new identity he decides to steal one and after considering a few options he decides on Bruce Wayne because their bodies are similar enough and he had learned many of Wayne's mannerisms while they were serving on the museum board together.

after getting plastic surgery to look like Bruce he ambushes Wayne as he is leaving a charity boxing match. taking his clothes he locks Bruce in an old bank vault and Goes "home" to Wayne Manor. as soon as he arrives Dick tells him commissioner Gordon has been calling and when "Bruce" asks what he wants Dick tells him he wants Batman and Robin in his office right away as he leads him down to the Batcave.

Moth is shocked by the irony that the identity he chose to steal belongs to Batman but he thinks fast and quickly assumes the role. soon they are in the police commissioner's office hearing him talk about mysterious truck hijackings by the Whitey Casey gang, a crime boss who refused to do business with Killer Moth so he sees this as a chance to fix him.

they figure out how the trucks are being hijacked and put a stop to it but only catch 2 of the gang. later, Killer Moth talks to the gang boss Casey and tells him next time flashes the Moth Signal it will send Batman running. the next night Batman and Robin catch the gang robbing a silk warehouse. they wrap up the gang in the silk they were trying to steal and chase Casey to the roof but when he flashes the signal Batman tells Robin to hurry back to the Batmobile, that there is no time to explain but he should wait there until he joins him. confused, Robin obeys and "Batman" quickly changes to Killer Moth to talk with Casey. he tells him he will deliver Batman to him at the location of the vault he has Bruce locked up in.

switching back to Batman he drives Robin to the vault and is surprised to see it open and Bruce is gone but he knocks robin out figuring he can at least deliver Robin. meanwhile, as Casey and his men approach the real Batman swings in and make short work of them before returning to the vault and being attacked by Robin who thinks he is the imposter. after convincing Robin he is the real Batman they head out to try and find the imposter.

Killer Moth, Back in his own outfit tries to get away but Casey wakes up just in time to see him, and thinking Moth set him up he shoots him full of holes. despite knowing he can reveal their secret, the dynamic duo rush Killer Moth to the hospital where the doctor saves his life but tells them his face was badly damaged and a bullet that was removed from his brain will make it unlikely he will remember any recent events.

2. The Terrible Toys Of Dr. Morro: (Robotman)

3. Jerry The Jitterbug: (humor strip by Henry Boltinoff)

4. The Man With The Golden Touch: (Impossible But True)

5. Quick Quiz: (4 panels of questions and answers)

6. Jerry The Jitterbug: (humor strip by Henry Boltinoff)

7. Murder Is A Fine Art: (text story)

8. Pow-Wow Smith -- Chief Of Police: (Pow-Wow Smith)

9. Varcity Vic: (humor strip by Henry Boltinoff)

10. Casey The Cop: (humor strip by Henry Boltinoff)

11. Look For The Real Reason: (Public Service Announcement with Binky Biggs)

description:
1. The Park Avenue Kid: (Batman) Bruce Wayne punches a fleeing robber, and the society press is amazed at his skill. A boxing promoter convinces him he'd be a sensation in the ring, and Bruce starts boxing as "The Park Avenue Kid". It's all a plan to bring a new gang leader, The Dagger, out into the open, as Batman suspected The Dagger was secretly one Ned Brann, another boxing promoter.
  2. Shorty: (gag strip by Henrey Boltinoff)
  3. The Strange Bodies of Robotman: (Robotman)
  4. Captain Tootsie: (Tootsie Roll add)
  5. Cacey The Cop: (gag strip by Henrey Boltinoff)
  6. The Man With The Bulletproof Heart: (Impossible but True)
  7. Casey The Cop: (gag strip by Henrey Boltinoff)
  8. White Mystery: (text story)
  9. Quick Quiz: (4 panels of questions and answers)
  10. The Legend of Stalking Ghost: (Pow-Wow Smith) Pow Wow Smith borrows fantastic tactics from the lore of his people in order to bring six desperate killers to justice.
  11. Varsity Vic: (gag strip by Henrey Boltinoff)

description:
1. The Underworld Bank: (Batman) convicted criminals keep saying they can't remember where they stashed the loot from their crimes but they are all found with a certain kind of key on them. Batman figures out they are safety deposit box keys but not to any known bank so they check with companies that make bank vaults and find the one matching the keys was sold for export but was actually installed under a warehouse that turns out to be a functional bank for the underworld.
  2. The Boy Who Re-made Robotman: (Robotman) While flying after some criminals Robotman is struck by lightning and crashes on a farm where a boy takes him apart and must put him back together before the criminals he was chasing find him.
  3. The Ghost Of Station WBT!: (Impossible-But True)
  4. Buzzy Says: Old Folks Are People, Too!: (PSA with Buzzy Brown)
  5. The Taming Of The Wild Bunch!:
  6. Our Footsore Nation: (text story)
  7. The Wampum Wigwam: (Pow-Wow Smith)
  8. Peg: (humor strip by Henry Boltinoff)
  9. Quick Quiz: (4 panels of questions and answers)

description:
1. Superman Says "The World Is Our Schoolroom!": (PSA)
  2. The Robberies In The Bat-Cave!: (Batman) Batman and Robin are working in the Batcave's crime lab when they find first their centrifuge, then their electron microscope missing. the next night they chase some criminals who were stealing oil from a tanker but the crooks get away using pontoon boots. returning to the Batcave the dynamic duo find their pontoon boots missing. after doing an inventory they find their Iodine Fume Gun also missing and worry that whoever is getting in to steal these things might know their secret. they set an electric eye at each entrance to the Batcave that will sound an alarm in their shared bedroom (which is shown to be spacious and have 2 beds but is still an odd choice). the next morning they find that despite the alarm not sounding their Helixometer was now missing. they then realize that with one exception the items were all used to prove the guilt of someone who got the chair while still claiming to be innocent. the exception was Monroe Peel who looked guilty based on evidence from the centrifuge and electron microscope but was declared innocent because he had an alibi and no motive. thinking Peel might somehow be responsible Batman goes to watch him while Robin maintains watch over the cave. while Batman is watching Peel the Bat-signal is lit. Batman must answer it so he leaves half-dollar coins at the front and back of the house and when they are still there upon his return he concludes Peel has not left the house. meanwhile, back in the cave, Robin decides to take a nap after his third patrol. around dawn, Peel finally leaves the house and Batman followed him to a place that rents refrigerated lockers for food storage before returning to the cave to wake Robin and find their Dactyloscope missing. the next night they again set the electric eye and go to sleep but Bruce wakes in the middle of the night to find Robin gone. it turned out the idea that had sent innocent men to the chair was causing Robin to sleepwalk and tossed the equipment they used in the river. Batman found Peel was guilty after all and showed Robin the other men were as well, curing him of his sleepwalking.
  3. Shorty: (humor strip by Hanry Boltinoff)
  4. The Man No Prison Door Could Hold: (Impossible But True)
  5. Robotman Meets Robotgirl: (Robotman)
  6. Quick Quiz: (4 panels of questions and answers)
  7. Keys For Any Kingdome: (text story)
  8. Trail Of The Secret Cave: (Pow-Wow Smith)
name: The Robberies in the Bat-Cave

description:
1. Lost -- A Free Education: (Leave It To Binky PSA) Binky asks his classmate Tim why he wasn't in school that day and Tim tells him he was lining up a job, he is quitting school and getting a job so he can make money and have fun now instead of more learning. Binky tells him he is making a mistake and a grocery store worker tells them Binky is right. He had the same idea 5 years ago but now he is stuck as an errand boy while his classmates who graduated all have good jobs with opportunities for advancement. now he is going to night school to catch up. Tim responds that maybe he should think it over and Binky closes with "Yes. everybody should think it over -- and remember that education is more than putting learning into your head. it makes a better person of you -- a more useful citizen, able to cope with the problems in life you'll be faced with!"
  2. The Underworld Crime Committee: (Batman) A crime boss called Mr. Velvet controls a national network but when it becomes clear someone is informing on them he abducts Robin and threatens him to get Batman to find the leaks in his organization.
  3. Casey The Cop: (humor strip by Henry Boltinoff)
  4. The Man Who Was 300,000 years old: (Impossible - But True)
  5. The Testing Of Robotman: (Robotman)
  6. Private Pete: (Humor strip by Henry Boltonoff)
  7. Vigilantes Of The Air Waves: (text Story)
  8. Grass From The Sky: (Pow-Wow Smith)
  9. Quick Quiz: (4 panels of questions and answers)

description:
1. Mayor Bruce Wayne: (Batman) At the same time Robin heads off to guard a secret Army atomic experiment Bruce is picked to fill in for the mayor of Gotham for a week during the real mayor's vacation. Batman is also named Man of the Year and is expected to be in a ceremony with the acting mayor. meanwhile, the thousandth person to figure out Bruce Wayne is probably Batman realizes he can't do both and impersonates Batman while Bruce is mayor.
  2. The Luckiest Man On Earth: (Imposamle But True)
  3. Robotman Crusoe: (Robotman)
  4. Frontier Photographer: (text story)
  5. The Reforming Of Little Elk: (Pow-Wow Smith)
  6. Casey The Cop: (humor strip by Henry Boltinoff)
  7. Shorty: (humor strip by Henry Boltinoff)
  8. Superboy Says "Share With Others": (PSA)

description:
1. Be Yourself -- Your Best Self: (PSA with Buzzy Brown)
  2. The Joker's Millions: (Batman) A well-known gang boss dies and leaves Jokermillions in cash and jewels. He goes straight and lives it up only to find that most of the fortune is fake. just when he thinks he has figured out a way to play it off with what he has left, the IRS shows up wanting taxes on the fortune they don't know is fake, causing Joker to take up crime again to keep up appearances. (that's right, the real villain of this story is the IRS.)
  3. Little Pete: (humor strip by Henry Boltinoff)
  4. The Man with the Cosmic Punch: (Impossible - But True)
  5. Captain Tootsie And The Radar Rescue: (Tootsie Roll add)
  6. Displays of Crime: (Robotman)
  7. Peg: (humor strip by Henry Boltinoff)
  8. Casey the Cop: (humor strip by Henry Boltinoff)
  9. Million-Dollar Burglaries: (text story)
  10. The Ghost Chief's Secret: (Pow-Wow Smith)

description:
1. "The Team's The Thing!": (Leave It To Binky PSA)
  2. The Crimes of the Human Magnet: (Batman) David Wist was a jeweler known for watch repair, tries to join a gang as a safe cracker but is laughed at because apparently, his skills are useless for big bank vaults. he tries to burglarise a mansion but sets off the alarm, summoning the dynamic duo. Fleeing them, Wist hops a fence and runs into an ultra-nuclear fission lab and causes an accident that turns him into a human magnet with a positive charge on his right hand and a negative charge on his left. unable to control the power he develops anti-magnetic plastic gloves to dampen the effect. he then makes a costume and begins a crime spree as the human magnet. in the end, Batman uses mosquitos to trick Wist into putting his hands together, rendering him helpless.
  3. Casey the Cop: (humor strip by Henry Boltinoff)
  4. Roy Raymond's Perfect Double: (Impossible But True) a man who seems to be Roy's double claims to be from the fourth dimension.
  5. Jerry The Jitterbug: (humor strip by Henry Boltinoff)
  6. The Safest Safe in the World: (Robotman)
  7. How Forgers Are Caught - New Secrets in the Handwriting Expert's Lab Foil the Criminals: (text story)
  8. Peg: (humor strip by Henry Boltinoff)
  9. Pow-Wow Smith, Medicine Man: (Pow-Wow Smith)
name: The Amazing Crimes of the Human Magnet

description:
1. The Human Puppets: (Batman) The dynamic duo faces a new crime boss who uses puppets to plan and rehearse his crimes. His puppets are so perfectly detailed he claims the face under the mask of his Batman puppet is the true face of Batman.
  2. Casey the Cop: (gag strip by Henry Boltinoff) Casey is saying how terrific his new radio set is because he can get emergency calls straight from headquarters when a sergeant walks by and asks if there are any calls from headquarters. He replied no but the Dodgers are winning six to one.
  3. The Man with the Arson Eyes: (Impossible but True) Roy's show is interrupted by a man who seems to cause anything he looks at without special goggles to burst into flame.
  4. Little Pete: (gag strip by Henry Boltinoff) Seeing Pete come home, his dad asks if his baseball game is over, to which he replies "No, Dad. I just came back for another ball." his dad then asks "Pete, what are you doing with a basketball? I thought you were playing baseball!" Pete replies "We are, Dad - but I figure we'll strike out less with this ball!"
  5. Robotman's Double: (Robotman) A mobster named Big John Doss tries to have a double of Robotman made so he can try to figure out how to defeat him.
  6. Jerry the Jitterbug: (gag strip by Henry Boltinoff)
  7. Who Discovered Fingerprints?: (text article)
  8. The Lawman Who Lost His Grip: (Pow-Wow Smith) Pow-Wow loses confidence after he is outsmarted by a pair of fugitives.
name: The Human Puppets! / The Man with the Arson Eyes / Robotman's Double / The Lawman Who Lost His Grip

description:
1. Happy Hobby Time: (PSA with Superboy)
  2. Famous Names Crimes: (Batman) To join Gotham's Namesake Club you must be named after a famous historical figure. After a man named Robin Hood is rejected because it was a nickname and not the namesake's real name, he storms off saying he hopes they all come to a bad end, just as their namesakes did. When members soon start dying in manners similar to their namesakes Hood is naturally suspected but turns out to be innocent. In fact, the club's vice president was killing them to get the money they had bequeathed to the club in their wills.
  3. Casey the Cop: (humor strip by Henry Boltinoff)
  4. The Man in the Iceberg: (Impossible but True) A man supposedly found frozen in an iceberg claims to be a pirate who knows the locations of 2 treasures. The first is on a rocky shore where they find a chest of old coins. the second is underwater and would cost $25,000 to salvage. The money is raised but when the gold is salvaged it turns out to be modern gold bars that had been stolen from an army ship by the "pirate" and his accomplices, who dropped it overboard when pursued.
  5. Varsity Vic: (humor strip by Henry Boltinoff)
  6. The Wrecking of Robotman: (Robotman)
  7. Phony Documents: (text story)
  8. Manhunt in Manhattan: (Pow-Wow Smith)

description:
1. Hop On the Welfare Wagon!: (public service message from Superman) A man tells Mr. Stanton that Superman will speak for their hospital fundraiser. He responds "Who needs a hospital in this town? I can take care of myself. I'm not giving a red cent, Superman or no Superman." Just then, Superman shows up saying he "has the wrong slant" and explaining that Americans have always helped each other when sickness and trouble came.

2. The Human Firefly (Batman) First appearance of the first Firefly. Self-described lighting-effects genius Garfield Lynns uses his skills to simulate a fire on the stage of a huge theater during a show so his men (disguised as ushers) can use the destruction to steal from the panicked crowd. Bruce and Dick are in the audience and quickly realize the fire isn't real. changing to the dynamic duo, they quickly calm the crowd, who realize that things have been stolen. Batman recognizes one of the ushers as a con named Linky who agrees to talk, saying he was just hired muscle on this job but before he can name his boss Lynns shoots him.

As Lynns flees, regretting killing Linky, our heroes manage to get on his car's roof. Noticing their shadows after he gets into the hills, Lynns wrecks his car trying to shake them off. He crawls from the wreck, trying to make it to the river so he can let the current carry him away and only makes it because his pursuers go the wrong way, seeing the light from a firefly and thinking it could be a cigarette. overhearing them say it was a firefly, Lynns decides that must be his lucky symbol and models a new identity on it.

Two weeks later, Firefly uses a bleaching light to make four paintings loaned to the Gotham Museum from the Louvre appear to lose their color. guards clear the room and his men come out of hiding to steal the paintings but Batman and Robin show up to foil the crime. Firefly and his men flee and are pursued by the Batmobile until Lynns uses his light belt to cause flashing lights that blind everyone behind his car, causing the Batmobiel to get caught in a traffic jam while he escapes.

The following night Firefly blacks out a lighthouse and uses his light belt to guide a freighter ship onto rocky sholes so his men can loot it. One of the crew starts to send out an S.O.S. before his men can stop it, causing Batman and Robin to show up and capsize Firefly's boat. He makes it to shore and flees to the lighthouse where he tricks our heroes, trapping them in the lighthouse basement. He then filled the room with blinding color from what he calls a Cyclops light. He tells them the battery will last three days and thinking they can't get out, thinks nothing of telling his men about a job they will pull at the airport that night while he is still close enough for the heroes to hear.

Using their capes to protect their eyes, Batman balances on Robin's feet to reach some wires on the ceiling that he is right to think feed power to the lighthouse lamp and use them to send out mosie code. Half an hour later, the coast guard arrives to free them. Almost an hour later Firefly is in an autogyro, shooting at a cargo plane when the Batplane shows up, uses the Cyclops light to blind the criminals, and hooks the autogyro, finally catching Firefly.

3. The Man Who Controlled the Elements: (Impossible but True) Aloysius Spanner claims his machine can control the weather. he produces first rain, then snow, and finally lightning but when Roy explains all of these away he proposes causing a small earthquake at noon the next day. Roy figures out that this is in fact a cover for an underground explosion that is used to break into a bank vault.

4. The Most Mysterious starrBook in the World: (text story)

5. Robotman Runs a Restaurant: (Robotman) Robotman helps a couple of ex-G.I.s who bought a dinner that is failing but once the place is thriving the crooked former owner wants it back.

6. The Indian Relic Robberies: (Pow-Wow Smith) A tribal museum is being opened in Red Deer Vally and the chief laments that they can't display three valuable relics owned by "palefaces". Smith goes to ask the owners if they can borrow the artifacts for the opening but they refuse. the artifacts are then stolen and left at the museum but these turn out to be fakes, the thefts having been staged for insurance money.

description:
1. "The Man Who Could Live Forever" featuring Batman and Robin

Odo Neval, a crook claiming to be a centuries old immortal, offers to sell the underworld his immortality elixir. Through a series of daring criminal activities, Neval proves that the formula works by demonstrating his own invulnerability. The crime lords of Gotham begin a crime wave to raise money to purchase the elixir. Batman captures one of them and takes his place. Batman then returns to Neval's hide-out, where he discovers the formula is fake. Before he can act the crooks knock him out. Robin bursts into the room and drinks the elixir. Thinking himself invulnerable, he pursues the crooks alone. When Batman recovers he races to reach Robin to inform him that the formula did not make him immortal. Batman reaches his partner in time and together they expose Neval, capturing him in the process.

2. "The Stars Spell Doom" featuring Roy Raymond TV Detective

3. "The Passenger Who Never Went Ashore" featuring Captain Compass

4. "The 3-D Crimes" featuring Mysto, the Magician Detective
name: The Man Who Could Live Forever

description:
1. The Puppet Master

Starring Batman and Robin. Jonathan Bard, a skilled puppeteer with no people skills, turns to a life of crime after being barred from a puppet contest for sabotaging his opponents equipment. Bard is able to rob a train by using life sized puppets to distract the guards while his gang pilfer the train's contents. Batman and Robin begin a manhunt for Bard who begins robbing armored cars using skyscraper sized puppets to distract the armored car guards. Batman and Robin chase Bard to his hideout but wind up in an elaborate death trap where they become marionettes under Bard's control. After toying with them, Bard leaves the Dynamic Duo to gather members of Gotham City's underworld for a puppet show featuring the death of Batman and Robin. When Bard returns the mob bosses quickly discover that the Batman and Robin on stage are live sized wooden puppets. Batman then leaps out from the ceiling and further humiliates the now disgraced criminal puppet master. Batman and Robin defeat Bard along with several of the Crime Lords in attendance. Script by Bill Finger, pencils by Dick Sprang, inks by Charles Paris.

2. Death at Ten Fathoms!

Starring Captain Compass, art by Joe Certa.

3. Mysto -- Country Slicker!

Starring Mysto Magician Detective, art by Leonard Starr.

description: The Case of The Magic Baseball - John Jones (Martian Manhunter, breaks his first few cases by using his Martian powers. One day, he is assigned a case in which he must keep an eye on Big Bob Michaels, who once served a prison term who has become a famous baseball pitcher for the Flamingos. Jones proceeds to investigate. Using his Martian telepathy, he finds out that Big Bob is being blackmailed by the mob. If he deliberately loses, he will be rewarded with money. If he wins, they will tell the world that he learned to pitch on a prison baseball team. In order to help out Michaels, John Jones uses his Martian Molecular Hypnosis and Martian Mind-Over-Matter abilities to help the Flamingos win. He then uses his invisibility to take out the mobsters who blackmailed Big Bob Michaels.

description: The Man With 20 Lives - Criminal Monte Fisk had escaped the law a score of times. But then, John Jones was put on the case. Using his Martian powers, he is able to read Fisk's mind and finds out that he is guilty of murder. He confronts Fisk, but since he had no solid evidence, he is unable to arrest him. Fisk decides John Jones is too close, so he orders his henchmen to assassinate John Jones. But since Jones cannot be harmed while in his extra-terrestrial form, they fail every time. Fisk eventually confesses thinking that John Jones is actually a ghost detective.

description: Bruce Wayne finds his fathers diary and comes to an entry where his father wears a costume resembling a bat at a Masquerade Ball. Bruce continues to read outloud to Dick Grayson "During the ball, hoodlums broke in demanding a doctor . They took me to a wounded Lou Moxon a bank robber who the police are currently searching for. Knowing that they would kill me after I patched up Moxon, somehow I managed, with a little luck to take down Moxon and his goons and turn them over to the police. When I attended Moxon's trial,he swore revenge and that he would get even with me as he was sentenced for ten years." Bruce checks further on into the diary discovering that ten years later after being released from prison, Moxon found and threatened his father, promising to kill him.Bruce Wayne reopens his parents murder case following a hunch that Moxon hired Joe Chill to kill his father. Later that night Batman and Robin visit Moxon at his Ski-Hi Advertising Co.. After tangling with Moxon and his gang, the Batman brings charges to the police that Moxon murdered Thomas Wayne. Moxon takes a lie detector test claiming he never even heard of a Thomas Wayne and passes it. Soon the Batman discovers that Moxon had gotten into a car accident and had a case of amnesia not too long after he threatened his father.The Batman guesses that Moxon may have forgotten some things but not in the way of crime and decides to tail him and his gang. After another go with Moxons gang Batman clothes are tattered and at Robins suggestion wears his fathers old "bat-man " costume to finally confront Lou Moxon. As the Batman enters Moxons place, a dread fear comes over Lou Moxon. It seems with the Batman wearing his fathers old Ballroom Bat costume has jarred some memories. Lou Moxon screams as though he is seeing a ghost," Your dead! I had Joe Chill kill you ! Leave me alone!" He starts running out of the building and into the oncoming traffic being killed instantly as he is struck by a truck.
name: The First Batman

description:
NIGHT OF THE BODY SNATCHER! Batman takes on the villainous ape Xavier Simon, whose plan is to place his mind inside Batmans body!

  1. Batcave
  2. Night of the Body Snatcher! (Batman) Reprinted in DC Goes Ape #1.
  3. A Quick Death in China! (Batgirl)
  4. The Eternity Book (The Demon)
  5. Bat-Mite's New York Adventure! (Bat-Mite)
  6. The League of Crime! (Robin)

description:
THE CURSE OF CRIME ALLEY. Batman takes on a new villain by the name of Maxie Zeus!

In this special anniversary issue of Detective Comics...

Batman must confront the demons of his past, a mass-murdering mobster, and The Curse of Crime Alley!

The Human Target must prevent an unscripted murderer in Hollywood when he takes on The Lights... Camera... Murder!" Contract!

Batgirl must root out a terrorist in the nation's capital, on a night she never expected when one lucky guy goes on "A Date With A Batgirl"!

Etrigan must fight for his very existence, but not even he can prevent a Return to Castle Branek!

Robin must put an end to MAZE once and for all in Terminus!

Bruce Wayne must... host "Gotham's Great Kangaroo Race!"

description:
Batman and Robin in "The Dynamic Trio"

When wanted American criminals begin showing up abroad, Gotham's mayor lays into Commissioner Gordon about the GCPD's inability to apprehend fugitives. The mayor demands that Batman and Robin take on the case. When Vicki Vale interviews Batman about the opportunity, the caped crusader reveals that he's bringing in a third person to help take down the ring of crook-smugglers, a new costumed crime fighter known as the Mysteryman. Shocked by the announcement, Vicki Vale vows to discover their new partners identity.

Roy Raymond in "The X-Y-Z Ray"

Martian Manhunter in "The Phantom Fire Alarms"

description:
The Man who Ended Batman's Career

A new Dynamic Duo of Starman and Robin appear in Gotham City. After foiling some criminals and returning to Wayne Manor, Bruce Wayne recalls how criminal scientist Professor Milo succeeded in giving Batman a phobia of bats, which caused him to adopt the costume and identity of Starman. Through a series of psychological experiments, Robin is able to cure Batman of his fear and together they defeat Milo and send him to jail.

Note - While Batman's adventure as Starman was removed from continuity after Crisis on Infinite Earths, in James Robinson Starman series he introduced the Starman of 1951, a superhero dressed in the same outfit who operated in the DC Universe in 1951.
name: The man Who Ended Batman's Career

description:
Batman's First Case

In Gotham City Park during the unveiling of a new "Batman Clock" to celebrate the heroes Batman and Robin, a costumed villain called The Clock appears, destroying the statue. The clock threatens Batman and then leaps to a hidden motorcycle and drives away. Batman recognizes his face.

A flash back sequence shows the death of Bruce Wayne parents at the hands of Joe Chill, a mugger who demanded Martha Wayne's necklace and then shot both Martha and Thomas Wayne. Bruce promised that he would dedicate his life to finding their killer, and to fighting all crime. He attended a school of criminology and trained his body to physical perfection. When he was ready for his career of crime-fighting, he knew he would need a disguise to instill fear in criminals. A bat flew into his window, and he took this as an omen. He would become a Batman.

The flash back then goes on to show the story of the first criminal Batman ever saw on patrol. Batman tangled with a thief and traced him to the abandoned Gotham Glass Works. The thief throws a net on Batman which teaches Batman to never underestimate a criminal. Batman is left tied up in the basement, but he uses a bucket of rouge to help him slip out of his bonds. Batman confronts the thief, and the thief shoots at him. It is revealed that Batman tricked the thief into shooting a mirror. Batman takes the thief out from behind, and explains his ruse.

Robin remembers reading this story about "Kyle" in Batman's Diary. They visit Kyle's former cellmate Tom Rogers for answers. Rogers explains that Kyle laughed at them for trying to go straight. Kyle developed an obsession with learning about clocks so he could use them to take revenge on Batman. This is supposed to be ironic, because Batman made him "do time" in prison. (We know, we know. I'm sorry.) The prison warden confirms that Kyle was incarcerated years ago at 3pm, which is why The Clock chose that time. The Clock sits in his hideout full of clocks and vows that just like he was Batman's first case, he will also be Batman's last. The Clock leaves another warning for Batman that his next caper will be "the tiniest clock crime." The Clock disguises himself as a reporter to visit the Gotham Watch Co. These watches are easily damaged by acid, and The Clock throws a pocketful of orange peels to distract the employees. While they're busy, he steals a bag of valuable tiny watch screws. Batman and Robin arrive. The Clock accidentally drops his watch while jumping out the window. They pursue him outside onto a giant clock. The Clock knocks Robin off his perch, and Batman is forced to save Robin while The Clock escapes. Batman investigates the dust inside The Clock's wristwatch, and finds an unusual amount of flour. This can only mean the abandoned flour mill outside of town. They step inside and an alarm clock goes off. The Clock reveals that he knew the watch would lead them to him, and he set a trap. The Clock knocks Batman and Robin out by dropping flour bags on them.

Batman wakes up tied to a clock. Wow, big surprise there. The Clock explains that Batman will die at 3pm when the clock he's tied to explodes. Then The Clock leaves. Robin is tied to a pole and forced to watch. Batman is still wearing The Clock's wristwatch and he swings back and forth to smash the wristwatch against a wall. Using the tiny broken shards, he cuts his bonds and they both escape. The Clock sees the explosion while he's driving away, and assumes Batman and Robin are dead. The Clock goes to Gotham City's Clock Fair, where a giant pocketwatch replica contains giant real jewels. Bursting out of a giant cuckoo clock, The Clock throws smoke capsules so he can steal the jewels. Batman and Robin rush in to stop him. The Clock tears off the pocketwatch's giant hour hand and uses it as a weapon. Batman kicks the mainspring housing, and The Clock becomes trapped inside its coils. Robin remarks that The Clock was caught by a clock. Exactly 1 hour and 13 minutes later, The Clock is back behind bars in prison. Batman visits him and remarks that they've given The Clock a cell that faces the prison clock
name: Batman's First Case

description:
The Raven and the Wasp. with Batman with Robin the Boy Wonder

Lefty Looie one page gag page

The Wizard King. with Roy Raymond TV Detective

Homicide in the Hothouse

Get a Grip on Your Gripes!

J'onn J'onzz's Kid Brother. with John Jones. Manhunter from Mars

Jonn J'onzz rebuilds the machine that Dr. Erdel invented (shown in cameo) that had caused him to accidentally bring J.J. to Earth, however instead of returning Jonn to Mars it brings his younger brother Tomm Jonzz to Earth.

Unfortunately the machine only has one charge so it can only be used once. We also get to see Mom & Dad Jonzz.

Of course in with typical Silver-Age logic it cant be recharged or rebuild or anything.
name: The Raven and the Wasp

description:
THE CHALLENGE OF CLAYFACE! The dynamic duo is part of a charity exchange where they encounter Clayface, a super-criminal with the power to change his body into any shape imaginable thanks to its clay-like constitution! Plus, THE MAN WHO IMPERSONATED JONN JONZZ. When Barry Clark, an impersonation artist imitating his friend Jonn Jonzz, sprains his ankle before attempting a grand comeback, the Martian Manhunter has no choice but to help his friend by impersonating him for his big moment on stage!

Batman: That fantastic Character, Clay-Face can mold his body into any shape!

In the Aquaman story, Aquaman has agreed to stand guard over a certain ship at sea. Diplomats from two warring nations are holding peace terms discussions. The ship's location is supposed to have been secret. But Aquaman has to face belligerent agents from both sides. Finally he investigates and discovers a transmitter which gave away the ship's location. He destroys it and keeps on protecting the diplomats.

Contents

  1. The Challenge of Clay-Face (Batman & Robin against Clayface (Matt Hagen, the 2nd Clayface : first appearance and origin - Matt finds a pool of chemicals)) / written by Bill Finger
  2. People Are People!
  3. The Man Who Impersonated J'onn J'onzz (John Jones Manhunter from Mars)
  4. Lefty Looie (gag strip)
  5. Man With the Badge
  6. The Secret Sentry Of The Sea (Aquaman and Aqualad)

description:
BATMAN: THE BIZARRE POLKA-DOT MAN. Batman and Robin confront a new costumed criminal in Gotham by the name of Mr. Polka Dot, who has started a crime wave based on spots and dots.

Batman and Robin battle Mr. Polka Dot. A criminal whose different polka-dots on his outfit become different weapons Batman and Robin must avoid.

The Aquaman series ends this issue. Actually it is transferred to "Worlds Finest Comics ", starting with issue #125.

description:
THE CONDEMNED BATMAN. Batmans body is altered by a scientific accident to make him radiate heat uncontrollably and to be only able to breathe methane gas, a condition the criminal Brains Beldon capitalizes on. Batman is forced to work from a special flying capsule against the crooks, who also try to eliminate the Dark Knight. During their last encounter, Batman tries to stop the criminals when he is struck by a high-tension cable.

description:
THE BRONZE MENACE. Batman, Robin and Batwoman tangle with a group of crooks who appear to be stealing bronze statues sculpted by Vulcan. After a long investigation, the heroes learn that Vulcan has been transforming people into bronze statues using a special machine, and after dealing with the criminals, he pretended to have the statues stolen. Batman and Robin are victims of Vulcans machine, but with Batwomans help, they are able to break free and capture the criminals.

Batman, Robin, and Batwoman tangle with a group of crooks who appear to be stealing bronze statues sculpted by Vulcan, but who are in reality the statues themselves.
name: The Bronze Menace

description:
THE RETURN OF CLAYFACE. Matt Hagen breaks jail again and uses his powers as Clayface to impersonate wealthy men in order to gain information for future crimes, which brings him into renewed conflict with Batman and Robin. However, Clayfaces powers are limited by time, and in order to keep working, Hagen takes a sample of the mysterious pool and starts investigating the element with a scientist he has kidnapped. Batman obsesses over Clayface, and his investigation leads him to the criminals secret hideout, where he learns of the chemical sample. Batman incorporates the chemical sample into a freezing gun, and with the weapon he is able to stop Clayface.

Matt Hagen breaks jail again and uses his power to impersonate wealthy men in order to gain information for future crimes, which brings him into renewed conflict with Batman and Robin.

description:
ALPHA, THE EXPERIMENTAL MAN! Batman and Robin help train Alpha, an artificial man created by Dr. Burgos, a scientist. But when he falls in love at first sight with Batwoman, Alpha uses the professors ray device to boost his intellect and power, a measure that may cause his death. As a result of his exposure to the ray, Alphas power levels are increased, but Burgos explains to Batman that it will destroy Alpha in the end if they cant take him back to the laboratory. When the heroes try to bring Alpha back, he refuses to go, believing that the humans have turned against him. Only Batwoman has the ability to convince Alpha that they are just trying to help him, but when Batwomans life is in peril, Alpha decides to save her by risking his own existence.

Batman and Robin help train Alpha, an artificial man created by Dr. Burgos, a scientist. But when he falls in love at first sight with Batwoman, Alpha uses the professors ray device to boost his intellect and power, a measure that may cause his death.
name: Alpha, the Experimental Man

description:
BAT-MITES SUPER-CIRCUS! Bat-Mite comes to Earth and gives three crooks superpowers to make them more challenging to Batman and Robin. But a bump on the head blocks Bat-Mite from using his powers against the crooks, and the three opponents may be more than the heroes can handle. The strongman, the rubber man and the human cannonball are unstoppable with their powers combined, and the heroes decide to take them out one by one.

description:
BATMAN: CHALLENGE OF THE CAT-MAN! Tom Blake, a playboy and big-game hunter, is inspired by the memory of the Catwoman and his pet black panther to become the Cat-Man, a costumed thief, using cat gimmicks and cat motifs in his robberies. Batman, Robin and Batwoman stand against Cat-Man and confront the criminal on a number of occasions until Batman is able to deduce Cat-Mans secret identity. When the Dynamic Duo find Cat-Mans lair, they fall into a trap, but Batman finds a way out, after which Cat-Man tries to escape, but falls into a nearby river and is dragged away by the current.

Tom Blake, a playboy and big-game hunter, is inspired by the memory of the Catwoman and his pet black panther to become the Cat-Man, a costumed thief, using cat-gimmicks and cat-motifs in his robberies. Batman, Robin, and Batwoman oppose him.
name: The Challenge of the Cat-Man

description:
BATMAN: THE SECRET OF CLAYFACES POWER! Matt Hagen breaks jail again and uses his pool of protoplasm to renew his Clayface identity. Using his powers, Hagen is unstoppable, until Batman follows him to the secret grotto where the pool is located. Batman and Hagen start fighting and both of them fall into the pool, after which they are both transformed into clay. Batman uses his new powers to become a Clayface-Batman in order to fight Clayface on even terms. At the end of the fight, Batman defeats Clayface and returns him to prison.

Matt Hagen breaks jail again and uses his pool of protoplasm to renew his Clayface identity. But Batman discovers the pool and uses it to become a Clayface-Batman in order to fight him on even terms.
name: The Secret of Clayface's Power

description:
DOUBLE BATMAN VS. DOUBLE X! Simon Ecks escapes from the sanitarium he was locked in with his memory restored. Ecks decides to develop another duplicator device and becomes Dr. Double X once again. He matches wits with Batman again, although this time, Batman is able to defeat him by generating an energy duplicate of himself with Ecks machine. Baman fights Ecks while their respective duplicates fight each other.

In order to combat Dr. X and his energy duplicate Dr. Double X, Batman subjects himself to a process that creates a Double Batman.

description:
THE FANTASTIC DR. NO-FACE! Dr. Paul Dent becomes a faceless criminal after a serious accident with a machine he created in order to erase scars from skin tissue.

The Fantastic Dr. No-Face

While demonstrating his new skin rejuvenation ray, Doctor Paul Dent suffers an accident that literally erases his face. Traumatized by his horrific appearance, Dent runs screaming into the night. Responding to the Bat-Signal, Batman and Robin find Dent, now calling himself "Doctor No-Face", shooting at movie posters in Gotham Square. Batman attempts to reason with Doctor No-Face. When a stray rifle shot brings a live electrical cable down into the street, Batman and Robin are distracted long enough for Doctor No-Face to escape. Doctor No-Face next appears at the Gotham Museum. Knocking out the night watchman with a gas capsule, Doctor No-Face begins torching portraits.

Alerted by a silent alarm, Batman and Robin intervene. Once again, Doctor No-Face escapes, this time by barring the Caped Crusaders' path with an enormous plaque. Doctor No-Face continues his bizarre crime spree across Gotham City, destroying the faces of clocks, statues and masks. Batman and Robin catch up to Doctor No-Face after he's already robbed the Gotham Jewel Exchange. Batman trails Doctor No-Face to a quarry, arriving just as the Faceless Fiend has thrown a valuable emerald into a rock-crusher. Though Batman upends the trough the emerald landed in, the gemstone is, nonetheless, crushed, destroying it's jeweled "face".

An offhand comment leads the Dynamic Duo to Mount Gotham. There, they find Doctor No-Face sandblasting the Batman Face Monument. Doctor No-Face severs Batman's line with the sandblaster. With Batman dangling from the monument's lips, Robin is quick to disengage the sandblaster's hose, before Doctor No-Face can fire the kill shot. With Doctor No-Face disarmed, Batman easily binds the Faceless Fiend, and carts him off to jail. Things, though, are not as they seem. Doctor No-Face is really Bart Magan, a career criminal. Magan approached Dent to have the scars removed from his face. When Dent refused, Magan subjected himself to the skin rejuvenation ray, erasing his own face.

Magan took the accident as an opportunity to frame Dent for his crimes. Batman, Robin and Police Commissioner Gordon expose Magan as the true face of Doctor No-Face. Magan failed to take into account Dent's extreme acrophobia. Dent could never have suspended himself at such an elevation to deface the monument. A quick fingerprint check uncovered Magan's identity. Rounding up Magan's criminal associates, Batman discovers that Doctor No-Face's destructive rampage was really a smokescreen to cover several robberies. The real emerald, as well as several valuable paintings are recovered. HIs ruse revealed, Magan faces a long sentence in Gotham Penitentiary.

J'onn J'onzz--Wizard Of 1463

Police detective John Jones takes a well-earned vacation to Europe. While exploring the Dolmain Caverns, Jones finds himself enveloped in mist. Jones finds the egress out of the cavern transports him to medieval Europe. Jones has arrived just in time to rescue Captain Louis Moray, who has been ridden off the edge of a ravine. Moray reveals that the Black Duke has abducted Prince Charles, and usurped the throne. Jones delivers Moray to a safe haven, then makes his way to the castle. Becoming intangible, Jones walks through the walls of the castle. Turning invisible, Jones eavesdrops on the Black Duke, to discern the prince's location.

The Black Duke sends out two of his guardsman to force the prince to abdicate the throne. Jones surreptitiously takes out one of the guardsmen, then takes on his appearance. Jones rides with the other guardsman to the prince's location, then takes down the Black Duke's guardsmen. Jones delivers the prince to Moray. Jones takes on the appearance of the prince, then engages the Black Duke's guardsmen in the town square. Jones defeats them all, while twisting their weapons into a giant pretzel shape. When word of the "prince's" actions reach the Black Duke, he takes matters in hand personally.

Catching the "prince" by surprise, the Black Duke clubs him into unconsciousness, then locks him in the castle dungeon. Weakened by the lit torches over the door, Jones decides to wait until morning, when the torches will be doused, to act. The real prince, along with Moray, rallies his people to rise up against the Black Duke. The Black Duke sends out his forces to meet the prince's head on. Moray sneaks into the dungeon and releases Jones. The Martian Manhunter engages the Black Duke's armies on the prince's behalf. With the Black Duke's surrender, the prince retakes the throne. Jones returns to present day Europe, then onward, back to America.
name: The Fantastic Dr. No-Face
