description:
Batman is forced to augment his costume yet again for his showdown with the deadly Gunhawk, who has taken an entire hospital hostage with a new prototype weapon.

Batman (Jean-Paul Valley) is trying out his new batsuit that fires two thousand razor-thin batarangs on some targets in the Batcave while Gunhawk rushes Bunny into an emergency room, threatening the staff with pistols.

The police surround the hospital while Batman rushes to the scene in the Batmobile, Gunhawk destroys a few cop cars with his new prototype gun. The Lieutenant in charge tries to negotiate with Gunhawk, with the intent to snipe him if he shows himself. Batman shows up and Gunhawk attacks. The two exchange rounds until Batman uses his flamethrower to send Gunhawk through the floor, gaining the upper hand. Desperate, Gunhawk tries to take a hostage only to find out its a dummy. SWAT enters the building, not knowing Batman is in the building. Out of ammo, Batman pounces on Gunhawk. SWAT blows into the room and distract Batman enough for Gunhawk to run away, the two tumble down the stairs and they both appear knocked out. Montoya and Bullock look on as Lt. Kitch reads Gunhawk his rights as he regains consciousness while Batman watches from a corner.

Notes:

  • The Deluxe Edition cover is of hard stock paper and it is foiled embossed in gold and blue.
  • Deluxe Edition cover price was $2.95.
  • Newstand Edition cover price was $1.50.
  • Both editions of the covers were penciled by Kelley Jones, inked by John Beatty and colored by Bob LeRose.
  • Jean-Paul Valley used the target range in the Batcave.
  • Jean-Paul Valley doesn't speak in this issue.
  • "DC Universe" one page featuring a memorial to the recent passing of Jack Kirby.

description:
Nightwing and Robin descend into the Batcave while Batman (Jean-Paul Valley) is away. Nightwing is upset that Jean Paul was picked over him to take up the mantle of Batman despite his past mental problems Bruce had assumed he was over. Robin explains Bruce thought Nightwing had moved on. A light appears in a tunnel and Nightwing prepares to battle what he believes to be Jean Paul.

Meanwhile in Gotham, Batman takes on some gun dealers and asks one of them where he can find LeHah. LeHah (or at least a hallucination of him) appears and Batman attempts to attack it while the arms dealer escapes.

Back in the Batcave the man in the tunnel is revealed to be Harold. Harold invites Robin and Nightwing down a shaft where they find his workshop where he has access to Valley's files. Robin finally learns how the new Batman has been getting around- the subway Bat-train.

High above Gotham on the tip of a skyscraper, Bruce Wayne wearing the mask of Tengu, struggles to get the nerve up to make a leap of faith off the building.

Meanwhile Batman tracks down one of the gun dealers who is bound in a dark basement and asks him about LeHah. The dealer assumes he's talking about one of the other dealers and tells him to go look for a guy named Candy in a club. Batman tells the dealer to stay awake or the rats will eat him.

Bruce takes on ninjas sent by Lady Shiva and they back him into a corner. Facing superior numbers he jumps off the side of a bridge, landing on a moving van, and rolls off to face another especially tall ninja master. They battle in traffic, Bruce takes special care not to kill any civilians in the process.

Batman abducts a man from the club that goes by the name Candy and takes him to a gun dealer's apartment. They find the dealer dead in his apartment, Batman suspects LeHah.

Bruce defeats the tall ninja, sending him into the windshield of a moving car, driven by another female ninja specializing in chains. She has Bruce on the ground nearly defeated when her chain gets caught on a moving truck dragging her away. He runs after her to make sure she survived while Lady Shiva looks on and smiles.

Police find the gun dealer that told Batman where to find Candy in the basement, petrified by the rats, screaming.

Back in the Batcave, Batman hallucinates again and sees St. Dumas who tells him that LeHah did not work alone in murdering his father. Robin and Nightwing watch from a monitor, as Valley loses his mind screaming to himself.

Notes:

  • A 48 page issue priced at $2.50.
  • Items visible in the Batcave are: the Diary of Dana Drye, the Hood of the Monk, the Gavel of Judge Clay, Case of the Prophetic Pictures (a picture), two large dice (in a case) a shirt (in a case), a small statue and a penguin.
  • On page 19 panel 3 newspaper headlines homages: "Ala- Gra- Fou- Sob-" (Alan Grant Found Sober?) = Alan Grant and "Dar- Vin- Win- Lot-" (Darren Vincenzo Wins Lottery?) = Darren Vincenzo.
  • On page 20 panel 4 Kirby Action Cereal is a homage to Jack Kirby.
  • On the same page as above "Sciantic Pain and Pregnancy Linked" and "Gunhawk Captured!"
  • Story continued from Batman: Shadow of the Bat #29.
  • Story continues in Batman: Legends of the Dark Knight #62.

description:
The issue opens with Nightwing in a rage, believing Batman (Bruce Wayne) to be dead he strikes at Jean Paul Valley who claims that Wayne's death proved that he is the one true Batman. Robin wonders aloud if Valley is the best Batman for Gotham City. A woman's baby is stuck in a car on fire but her cries are ignored by Nightwing and Valley as they trade blows. Robin saves the child moments before the car explodes, sending him tumbling. He tells a police officer to clear the bridge, the Batmobile has exploded.

Nightwing and Valley fight to the edge of a bridge and Valley pulls them both over. Nightwing saves them both using Valley's grappling hook in his armor but the rope snaps and they plummet into the water below. Batman (Bruce Wayne) emerges from the fire of the Batmobile and tells Robin to leave Nightwing.

At the bottom of the bay Nightwing frees himself from Valley and swims up to a party boat. Bullock and Montoya arrive and deduce that there's a battle to see who will be Gotham's Batman. Valley beat Nightwing to the boat and yanks him on board. The two fight, busting through walls and ruining gambler's poker games. Valley threatens to kill Nightwing and then Robin afterwards. Valley gains the upper hand and is about to finish off Nightwing after knocking him out on a slot machine when two police officers order him to stop. He throws Nightwing into the officers and escapes back to the Batcave. Ranting to himself and to St. Dumas that he has taken back the city, Valley notices someone in the mansion above, only its not Robin as he believed, but Bruce Wayne waiting for him.

Notes:

  • Story continued from Batman: Shadow of the Bat #30.
  • Story continues in Batman: Legends of the Dark Knight #63.

description:
1. Slam Bradley [2] Skyscraper Death: Slam is accused of the murder of Pete Graves, a steelworker he had been sparring with earlier. When Shorty tails Grave's lawyer, he discovers the truth behind a rackeeteering ring in the area and it's up to Slam to rescue him from being thrown off the Jinx Tower.
  2. Buck Marshall, Range Detective [2] The Sage City Bank Holdup: The blowing up of a local dam leads Buck to the discovery of a gang lead by Taft, "an honest businessman" and president of the Sage City Bank.
  3. Gumshoe Gus [2] The Disappearing Duck: Gus is sent to investigate the disappearance of the Beekman's pet duck Gloria, only to find she's flown the coop for a famous Disney duck who makes her breast feathers quiver.
  4. Bret Lawton - The Peruvian Mine Murders Part 2: With the death total now at 8 men, Bret continues his search. When he gets too close to a presumed extinct Incan tribe, he finds himself neck deep in sand, with a face smeared with honey for the jungle ants to feast on.
  5. Room Fifteen: Musical colors rule the day as White and more extend room fifteen's stay.
  6. Bart Regan, Spy [2] The Balinoff Case Part 2: Bart must crack the mystery of Olga's bronze statue while watching his ex-fiance get married to an old suitor.
  7. Mail-Order Murphy: Humor two-pager about a neophyte detective finding an apple pie.
  8. Mr. Chang [1] The Narcotic Ring: Chang is called in to investigate a narcotic's ring that has captured two reporters assigned to the story. Fisticuffs and day-saving ensues.
  9. Cosmo, The Phantom in Disguise [2] The Olive Oil Counterfeiters: Cosmo is called in to investigate a counterfeiting ring that has perplexed the department's top detectives. He cracks the case by disguising himself as an old man and getting a job in the gang.
  10. Bruce Nelson [2] The Claws of the Red Dragon Part 2: Captured by the Chinamen, Bruce is stuffed into a car and dropped off deep into the country. Making his way back to New York City, he finds the restaurant empty, but follows a real estate lead to Long Island.
  11. Silly Sleuths: A collection of one-panel jokes.

description:
1. Speed Saunders and the Mystery of San Jos Island [4] (by Fless, Creig Flessel)

2. Untitled Gag

3. Cosmo, The Phantom of Disguise [4] (illustrated by Sven Elvn)

4. Buck Marshall, Range Detective [4] Death Message (by Homer Fleming)

5. Bruce Nelson [4] The Claws of the Red Dragon part 4 (by Tom Hickey)

6. The Evil Oak (text story by Paul Dean, illustrated by Creig Flessel)

7. The Bumps Mystery (by Alger, Russell Cole)

8. Bart Regan Spy part 4 (by Jerry Siegel & Joe Shuster)

9. Mr. Chang [2] The Bloody Will (by Win, Ed Winiarski)

10. Slam Bradley [4] The Hollywood Murders (by Jerry Siegel & Joe Shuster)

description:
Meet the all-new Ventriloquist! After surviving a near-fatal explosion, Batman discovers the Ventriloquist and Scarface are back - with a vengeance. As the Dark Knight tries to unravel the mystery behind his enemies' resurrection, Scarface unites the most feared names in the Gotham Underworld and introduces them to a surprising new ally in their war against Batman.

Arnold Wesker, the ventriloquistwas supposed to be dead. But Scarface, the tough talkin' machinegun totin'mannequin, has reappeared. Abeautiful woman in a red dress, "Sugar,"has become Scarface's new act. She's a blonde bombshell in more ways than one.
name: Double Talk

description:
Zoologist Kirk Langstrom is working late at the Gotham Natural History Museum putting together a bat habitat; he aims to perfect a serum that can endow people with enhanced auditory abilities via a specialized bat gland extract. Pleased with his progress, he decides to test his new formula upon himself, mutating him into Man-Bat.

  1. Challenge of the Man-Bat (Batman vs Man-Bat (1st appearance) / written by Frank Robbins)

  2. A Burial for Batgirl (Batgirl, Robin / written by Dennis J. O'Neil)
name: Challenge of the Man-Bat ; A Burial for Batgirl

description:
1. Speed Saunders and the River Patrol [3] A Stowaway in Need: Speed's vacation on Long Island Sound is cut short when he discovers a beautiful young stowaway. She's hid there from ne'er-do-well "Spider" Liverman who wants the plans for a typewriter her dead brother invented. When Spider catches up with Speed on the open water, it's swim, sink, and win.
  2. Hope Hazard - The Air Mail Mystery Part 1: Hope Hazard is called in to determine why three plans worth of air-mail has mysteriously disappeared. When she boards the fourth, it has to make an emergency landing in an isolated mountain range, where they discover "the headquarters of Xavier!! - Ruler of the Underworld!!"
  3. Cosmo, The Phantom in Disguise [3] The Kidnapping of Angus MacDonald: Owner and president of a steamship company, MacDonald is brashly kidnapped in front of his sumptuous home, with no one the wiser... save a little girl playing nearby. Cosmo disguises himself as MacDonald, shows up for a board meeting, and surprises the truth out of conspirator.
  4. Bruce Nelson [3] The Claws of the Dragon Part 3: WIth the haunting memory of Sigrid's beauty driving him forward, Bruce heads into the House of the Lion only to be stalked by five murderous-looking Chinese.
  5. The Wales Case: It's fifty eyewitnesses to three that says Bell did the deed, only for "Lazy" Smith to come out and proclaim another seed!
  6. Bart Regan, Spy [3] The Nearly-Weds: Olga Balinoff kidnaps Bart's ex-fiance Sally on her wedding day and demands she give up Bart's name and whereabouts. When the police force think Bart kidnapped her out of jealously, Bart must both clear his name and save his sweetheart.
  7. Buck Marshall, Range Detective [3] Bullets in the Dark: Buck captures Bull Leary, an outlaw he's been tracking over three states. It turns out Bull's been involved in a cattle thieving operation and when Buck pretends to be him to investigate further, he nearly gets himself shot to death.
  8. Slam Bradley [3] Slam Delivers the Message: Slam is promised the hefty sum of two hundred dollars if he delivers a sealed envelope. When he arrives at his contact's destination he's immediately pick-pocketed, though Shorty does a little pick-pocketing of his own to return it to Bradley. However, Shorty being Shorty, he loses it again and it's a chase to retrieve the secret message, a chase that ends in a double-cross!

description:
Stories:

  1. Slam Bradley [5] Undercover In Grade School (by Jerome Siegel & Joe Shuster)

  2. Buck Marshall Range Detective [5] The Path Of Thorns (by H. Fleming)

  3. Bruce Nelson [5] The Claws Of The Red Dragon Part 5 (by Tom Hickey)

  4. Winged Death (text story by Fredric Wells, illustrated by Creig Flessel)

  5. The Elm Park Mystery (by Alger, Russell Cole)

  6. Spy [5] The Balinoff Case Part 5 (by Jerome Siegel & Joe Shuster)

  7. Cosmo, The Phantom of Disguise [5] The Dope Torpedo (illustrated by Sven Elvn)

  8. Larry Steele [1] Mystery Of The Wholesale Kidnappings: Part 1 (by Will Georgi, Will Ely)

  9. Speed Saunders [5] A Most Fishy Robbery (by Fless, Creig Flessel)

  10. Silly Sleuths

description:
Stories:

  1. Speed Saunders [6] The Mystery Of The Lost Ape

  2. The Law At Work [1]

  3. Larry Steele [2] Mystery Of The Wholesale Kidnappings Part 2 (by Will Georgi aka Will Ely)

  4. Cosmo, The Phantom of Disguise [6] The Disappearing Diamonds (illustrated by Sven Elvn)

  5. Bruce Nelson [6] The Claws Of The Red Dragon: Part 6 (by Tom Hickey)

  6. Tropical Trouble (text story by Paul Dean, illustrated by Creig Flessel)

  7. Gumshoe Gus [3] A Bum Disguise (by Bill Patrick)

  8. Spy [6] The Investigation Of Captain Hanley (by Jerome Siegel and Joe Shuster)

  9. Mr. Chang [3] The Mad Scientist (by Win aka Ed Winiarski)

  10. Slam Bradley [6] In Mexico (by Jerome Siegel and Joe Shuster)
name: The Mystery of the Lost Ape

description:
Malcolm Wheeler-Nicholson - Editor and Publisher

Vincent A. Sullivan, F. Whitney Ellsworth - Associate editors

Stories:

  1. Slam Bradley [7] In Atlantic City (by Jerome Siegel and Joe Shuster)

  2. Cosmo, The Phantom of Disguise [7] The Premonition Of Emil Rogello (illustrated by Sven Elvn)

  3. Bruce Nelson [7] The Claws Of The Red Dragon Part 7 (by Tom Hickey)

  4. Rifles on The River (text story by Guy Monroe, illustrated by Creig Flessel)

  5. Gumshoe Gus [4] The Mystery Play (by Bill Patrick)

  6. Spy [7] The Colossus Disaster (by Siegel and Schuster)

  7. Buck Marshall Range Detective [7] A Report - In Detail (by H. Fleming)

  8. Larry Steele [3] Mystery Of The Wholesale Kidnappings Part 3 (by Will Ely)

  9. Speed Saunders at the Rodeo [7]

  10. Silly Sleuths

description:
Stories:

  1. Speed Saunders and The River Patrol [8] (by Fless [aka Creig Flessel])

  2. The Law Wins [1]

  3. Larry Steele Private Detective [4] Mystery Of The Wholesale Kidnappings Part 4 (by Will Ely)

  4. Cosmo, The Phantom of Disguise [8] The Disappearance Of Carl Huntley (illustrated by Sven Elvn)

  5. Bruce Nelson [8] The Claws Of The Red Dragon Part 8 (by Tom Hickey)

  6. The Laughing Mummy (text story by Paul Dean, illustrated by Creig Flessel)

  7. Bloodhound Brown (by Alger [aka Russell Cole])

  8. Spy [8]- The Phony Pierre Blanc (by Jerome Siegel and Joe Shuster)

  9. Buck Marshall Range Detective [8] Lucky Hunch (by H. Fleming)

  10. Slam Bradley -[8] The Hillbillies (by Jerome Siegel and Joe Shuster)

description:
Malcolm Wheeler-Nicholson - Editor and Publisher

Vincent A. Sullivan, F. Whitney Ellsworth - Associate Editors

Stories:

  1. Speed Saunders [9] Case Of The Hobo Hero (by Creig Flessel)

  2. Sgt. Simp

  3. Larry Steele Private Detective [5] Mystery Of The Wholesale Kidnappings Part 5 (by Will Ely)

  4. Cosmo, The Phantom of Disguise [9] Death In The Radio-Studio (illustrated by Sven Elvn)

  5. Bruce Nelson [9] The Blood Of The Lotus Part 1 (by Tom Hickey)

  6. Death at Latitude 30 (text story by Fredric Wells, illustrated by Creig Flessel)

  7. The Johnson Mystery (by Alger [aka Russell Cole])

  8. Spy [9] The Vanishing Of R-42 (by Jerome Siegel and Joe Shuster)

  9. Buck Marshall Range Detective [9] Silver and Lead (by H. Fleming)

  10. Slam Bradley [9] The Human Fly (by Jerome Siegel and Joe Shuster)

description:
Malcolm Wheeler-Nicholson - Editor and Publisher

Vincent A. Sullivan, F. Whitney Ellsworth - Associate Editors

Stories:

  1. Speed Saunders Ace Detective [10] Mystery at Oak Gables (by Creig Flessel)

  2. The Law Wins [2]

  3. Larry Steele, Private Detective [6] The Nick Orsatti Case Part 1 (by Will Ely)

  4. Cosmo, The Phantom of Disguise [10] Curse Of The Indian Mummy (illustrated by Sven Elvn)

  5. Bruce Nelson [10] The Blood Of The Lotus Part 2 (by Tom Hickey)

  6. Green Death (text story by Vincent Sullivan)

  7. Handcuff Hawkins (by Alger aka Russell Cole)

  8. Spy [10] To Sink The Atlantis (by Jerome Siegel and Joe Shuster)

  9. Buck Marshall Range Detective [10] Trail Of Yellow (by H. Fleming)

  10. Slam Bradley [10] In The Ring (by Jerome Siegel and Joe Shuster)

  11. The Law At Work [2] George Barrett, Kentucky Killer

description:
1. Robin the Boy Wonder - When Boss Zucco's protection racket leads to the death of circus performers John and Mary Grayson, Batman helps their son, Dick, avenge the murders. (Batman)
  2. The Electrical Assassin (Bart Regan, Spy)
  3. Dr. Hydkil (Red Logan)
  4. Phoney Jewel Robbery (Crimson Avenger)
  5. Kidnapped [Monthly Book Review]
  6. The Kidnapped Singer (Speed Saunders, Ace Investigator)
  7. The Gambler's Protector (Steve Malone, District Attorney)
  8. At The Artic Circle (Cliff Crosby)
  9. The Case of the Vanishing Train by Richard Martin (text)
  10. The Big Fire (Slam Bradley)

This is the first appearance of Robin and gives his (Dick Grayson's) origin story.
name: Introducing Robin, The Boy Wonder

description:
Malcolm Wheeler-Nicholson - Editor and Publisher

Vincent A. Sullivan, F. Whitney Ellsworth - Associate Editors

Stories:

  1. Speed Saunders of the River Police [11] The Anarchist Submarine Plot (by Creig Flessel)

  2. The Law At Work [3] The Power Behind "Machine Gun" Kelly

  3. Larry Steele [7] The Nick Orsatti Case Part 2 (by Will Ely)

  4. Cosmo, The Phantom of Disguise [11] The Phony Murder Of Sir Fenton Carsley (illustrated by Sven Elvn)

  5. Bruce Nelson [11] Bulls Eye (by Tom Hickey)

  6. Incident In Algiers (text story by Whitney Ellsworth)

  7. The Willow Lane Mystery (by Alger aka Russell Cole)

  8. Spy [11] The Atlantis Aftermath (by Siegel and Shuster)

  9. Buck Marshall, Range Detective [11] In The Bag (by H. Fleming)

  10. Slam Bradley [11] The Flying Circus (by Jerome Siegel and Joe Shuster)

  11. Sir Hubert Wilkens Famous Arctic Explorer (by Will Ely)

description:
Stories:

  1. Dr. S. G. Boyce (illustrated by Gill Fox)

  2. Speed Saunders, Ace Ivestigator and The Mystery Of Hondoku Isle [14] (by Creig Flessel)

  3. The Law at Work [4] Eddie Doll (by Will Ely)

  4. Buck Marshall Range Detective [14] Framing The Framers (by H. Fleming)

  5. Larry Steele, Private Detective [11] The Jenks Kidnapping Case Part 3 (by Will Ely)

  6. Bruce Nelson [14] Too Many Crooks Part 1 (by Tom Hickey)

  7. Oil from China (text story by Paul Dean, illustrated by Creig Flessel)

  8. The Black Case (by Alger aka Russell Cole)

  9. Spy [14] The Golden Ray (by Siegel and Shuster)

  10. Hot Trail Hogan (by Alger aka Russell Cole)

  11. Cosmo, The Phantom of Disguise [14] The Poultry Racketeers (illustrated by Sven Elvn)

  12. Slam Bradley [14] Up North (by Jerome Siegel and Joe Shuster)

  13. Quentin Roosevelt, Heroic Fighter (by Will Ely)

description:
Stories:

  1. Speed Saunders [15] The Mystery Of The Darby Pearls (by Creig Flessel)

  2. Oscar The Gumshoe [1] (by Bob Kane)

  3. Buck Marshall, Range Detective [15] Heels and Toes (by H. Fleming)

  4. Larry Steele, Private Detective [12] The Plot To Kill Larry Steele Part 1 (by Will Ely)

  5. Bruce Nelson [15] Too Many Crooks Part II (by Tom Hickey)

  6. Lightning Strikes Once (text story by Paul Dean, illustrated by Creig Flessel)

  7. Spy [15] Mr. Death (by Siegel and Shuster)

  8. "Bring 'Em In" Brannigan (by Alger aka Russell Cole)

  9. Cosmo, The Phantom of Disguise [15] The Plane Crash Mystery (illustrated by Sven Elvn)

  10. Slam Bradley [15] The Lady-Killer (by Jerome Siegel and Joe Shuster)

  11. Ruth Harkness: Her Adventures In The Far East (by Will Ely)
name: The Mystery of the Darby Pearls

description:
Stories:

  1. Speed Saunders and The Case Of The Missing Corpse [16]

  2. Black Tony Barmacino: Dictator Of The Dope Dynasty

  3. Larry Steele, Private Detective [13] The Plot to Kill Larry Steele Part 2 (by Will Ely)

  4. Cosmo, The Phantom of Disguise [16] The National Museum Mystery (illustrated by Sven Elvn)

  5. Bruce Nelson [16] Too Many Crooks Part 3 (by Tom Hickey)

  6. The Tattoo Trap (text story by Paul Dean)

  7. Spy [16] A Traitor In Our Midst (by Siegel and Shuster)

  8. "Fingerprint" Farson, The Plain Clothes Man (by Alger aka Russell Cole)

  9. Buck Marshall, Range Detective [16] Trading Trouble (by H. Fleming)

  10. Slam Bradley [16] The Broadway Bandit (by Jerome Siegel and Joe Shuster)

description:
Stories:

  1. Speed Saunders Ace Investigator and The Snake Death [17] (by Fred Guardineer)

  2. Oscar The Gumshoe [2] (by Bob Kane)

  3. Larry Steele Private Detective [14] The Maine Castle Mystery Part 1 (by Will Ely)

  4. Cosmo, The Phantom of Disguise [17] Von Ruyter's Explosive Gun (illustrated by Sven Elvn)

  5. Doctor Fu Manchu! [Part 1] (by the celebrated English author Sax Rohmer)

  6. Spy [17] The Hooded Hordes (by Jerome Siegel and Joe Shuster)

  7. Disaster on The Diamond (text story by Paul Dean)

  8. Bruce Nelson and The Coolie Smugglers Part 1 [17] (by Tom Hickey)

  9. Buck Marshall, Range Detective [17] The Right Trail (by H. Fleming)

  10. Slam Bradley Gets The Air [17] (by Siegel and Shuster)

  11. Detective Puzzles (by A.W. Nugent)
name: The Snake Death

description:
Stories:

  1. Speed Saunders and The Hilton Diamond [18] (by Fred Guardineer)

  2. Oscar The Gumshoe [3] (by Bob Kane)

  3. Cosmo, The Phantom of Disguise [18] Murder In Texas (illustrated by Sven Elvn)

  4. Larry Steele, Private Detective [15] The Maine Castle Mystery Part 2 (by Will Ely)

  5. Doctor Fu Manchu! [Part 2] (by the celebrated English author Sax Rohmer)

  6. Spy [18] Death's Ruby (by Siegel and Shuster)

  7. The Golden Key (text story by Paul Dean)

  8. Bruce Nelson and The Coolie Smugglers Part II [18] (by Tom Hickey)

  9. Steve Malone, District Attorney [1] The Lavalle Case

  10. Slam Bradley [18] In The Stratosphere (by Jerome Siegel and Joe Shuster)

  11. Detective Puzzles

description:
Stories:

  1. Speed Saunders Ace Investigator and The Grogan Case [19] (by Fred Guardineer)

  2. Crime Never Pays [1] (by Don Vincent aka Vincent Sullivan)

  3. Inspector Kent of Scotland Yard [1] The Invisibility Formula (by George Newman)

  4. Larrry Steele Private Detective [16] The Island Of Wanatoba Part 1 (by Will Ely)

  5. Spy [19] Mirror Of Doom (by Siegel and Shuster)

  6. Doctor Fu Manchu! [Part 3] (by the celebrated English author Sax Rohmer)

  7. A Dead Case (text story by Paul Dean)

  8. Bruce Nelson and The Coolie Smugglers Part 3 [19] (by Tom Hickey)

  9. Cosmo, The Phantom of Disguise [19] The Air Pirates and The S.S. Almoa (illustrated by Sven Elvn)

  10. Steve Malone District Attorney [2] Luigi Ferrini Strikes

  11. Slam Bradley [19] In Africa (by Jerome Siegel and Joe Shuster)

  12. Detective Puzzles

description:
Stories:

  1. Speed Saunders and The Jade Buddha [20] (by Fred Guardineer)
  2. Stamps Collectors' Corner (text article)
  3. Larry Steele Private Detective [17] The Island of Wanatoba Part 2 (by Will Ely)
  4. Buck Marshall, Range Detective [18] The Door of Death (by H. Fleming)
  5. Spy [20] Saving Senator Barkley (by Siegel and Shuster)
  6. Doctor Fu Manchu! [Part 4] (by the celebrated English author Sax Rohmer)
  7. Give and Take (text story by Paul Dean)
  8. Bruce Nelson and the Song of Death, Part 1 [20] (by Tom Hickey)
  9. The Crimson Avenger [1] Block Buster (by Jim Chambers)
  10. Cosmo, The Phantom of Disguise [20] Boat Race of Doom (illustrated by Sven Elvn)
  11. Slam Bradley [20] The Magician (by Jerome Siegel and Joe Shuster)

description:
While Batman is cutting his way through the thugs of Gotham City, he thinks back to his past. He remembers his parents murder; his creation of the identity of the Batman; his acquisition and redesign of the first Batmobile from Wayne Enterprises; his exploration of the Batcave; his design of the Batarang and the Utility Belt; and his first run-in with the wide variety of villains that make up his rogues gallery. In the present, Batman eventually finds the two child hostages he was looking for. He makes short work of the kidnappers, and rescues the children, proving himself Gotham Citys protector.

Notes:

  • "This issue is dedicated to Neal Pozner."
  • The letter column contains a half page text piece on the death of Neal Pozner.
  • John Wren credited as "pawed shamelessly."
  • Except for Batman all characters have cameo flashback appearances.
  • A Zero Month crossover issue.

description:
Stories:

  1. Speed Saunders Ace Investigator and The Glass Of Poison [21] (by Fred Guardineer)
  2. Crime Never Pays [2]
  3. Larry Steele, Private Detective [18] The Accident Racket (by Will Ely)
  4. Buck Marshall Range Detective [19] Bullet Trap (by H. Fleming)
  5. Spy [21] The Affair Of Baron Von Muldorf (by Siegel and Shuster)
  6. Doctor Fu Manchu! [Part 5] (by the celebrated English author Sax Rohmer)
  7. The Crime In Stone (text story by Paul Dean)
  8. Bruce Nelson and The Song Of Death, Part 2 [21] (by Tom Hickey)
  9. The Crimson Avenger [2] Mystery at The Mt. Pleasant Cemetary (by Jim Chambers)
  10. Steve Malone District Attorney [3] The Pigeon Smugglers
  11. Slam Bradley [21] Seth and The Slave Ring (by Jerome Siegel and Joe Shuster)

description:
Stories:

  1. Slam Bradley [22] The Return Of Fui Onyui (by Jerome Siegel and Joe Shuster)
  2. Larry Steele, Private Detective [19] Mansion Of Maniacs (by Will Ely)
  3. The Crimson Avenger [3] Wanted, Dead or Alive (by Jim Chambers)
  4. Bruce Nelson and the Song of Death [Part 3] [22] (by Tom Hickey)
  5. A Sticky Clue (text story by Paul Dean)
  6. Bob Showed Them How Spies Work (Chemcraft comic-ad)
  7. Spy [22] Break-In at The Bartilian Embassy (by Siegel and Shuster)
  8. Secret Service (by Fred Wells)
  9. Edward O. Heinrich
  10. Doctor Fu Manchu! [Part 6] (by the celebrated English author Sax Rohmer)
  11. Oscar The Gumshoe [4] (by Bob Kane)
  12. Stamps Collectors' Corner (text)
  13. Cosmo, The Phantom of Disguise [22] Bonelli The Jewel Thief (illustrated by Sven Elvn)
  14. Inspector Kent of Scotland Yard [2] The Return Of The Raven (by George Newman)
  15. Speed Saunders and The Snow Murder [22] (by Fred Guardineer)
  16. Crime-Curiosities

description:
Stories:

  1. Speed Saunders and The Ski Murder [23] (by Fred Guardineer)
  2. Crime Never Pays [3]
  3. Larry Steele, Private Detective [20] The Corpse In The Car Trunk (by Will Ely)
  4. Buck Marshall Range Detective [20] Nuggets Of Lead (by H. Fleming)
  5. The Crimson Avenger [4] The Zombie Killers (by Jim Chambers)
  6. Bruce Nelson [23] Gambler's Waterloo (by Tom Hickey)
  7. Railroad Riddle (text story by Paul Dean)
  8. Spy [23] The Celebrity Deaths (by Jerry Siegel and Joe Shuster)
  9. The Mysterious Doctor Fu Manchu! [Part 7] (by Sax Rohmer)
  10. Kops and Robbers (by Bob Kane)
  11. Stamps Collectors' Corner (text)
  12. Cosmo, The Phantom of Disguise [23] The Many Murder Attempts Of McQuade (illustrated by Sven Elvn)
  13. Slam Bradley [23] In Two Billion A.D.: Part 1 (by Jerome Siegel and Joe Shuster)
  14. Detective Puzzles

description:
Stories:

  1. Detective Puzzles
  2. Speed Saunders Ace Investigator and The Death Sled [25] (by Fred Guardineer)
  3. Crime Never Pays [5]
  4. Larry Steele, Private Detective [22] The Model Murder Mystery, Part 2 (by Will Ely)
  5. Buck Marshall, Range Detective [22] Death Masquerades (by H. Fleming)
  6. Spy [25] The President's Assignment (by Jerry Siegel and Joe Shuster)
  7. Oscar The Gumshoe [6] (by Bob Kane)
  8. Stamp Collectors' Corner (text)
  9. The Mysterious Doctor Fu Manchu! [Part 9] (by Sax Rohmer)
  10. Secret Service Man (text story by Paul Dean)
  11. The Crimson Avenger [6] The Airline Insurance Murders (by Jim Chambers)
  12. Bruce Nelson in Back from The Dead, Part 2 [25] (by Tom Hickey)
  13. Cosmo, The Phantom of Disguise [25] Ma Pierce's Last Kidnapping (illustrated by Sven Elvn)
  14. Slam Bradley [25] The Merrivale Mystery (by Jerry Siegel and Joe Shuster)

description:
Stories:

  1. Slam Bradley [26] Artists Of Death (by Jerry Siegel and Joe Shuster)
  2. Steve Malone District Attorney [4] The Van Dorn Murder Case
  3. Bruce Nelson in Back from The Dead, Part 3 [26] (by Tom Hickey)
  4. The Crimson Avenger [7] The Phony Crimson Avenger (by Jim Chambers)
  5. Disguise (text story by Paul Dean)
  6. Larry Steele Private Detective [23] The Taxicab War (by Will Ely)
  7. The Mysterious Doctor Fu Manchu! [Part 10] (by Sax Rohmer)
  8. Stamp Collectors' Corner (text)
  9. Cleo and Clancy [2] (by Bob Kane)
  10. Rosati accordion comic-ad
  11. Cosmo, The Phantom Detective [26] The Fake Shipwreck (illustrated by Sven Elvn)
  12. Spy [26] The Man Who Torpedoed Congress (by Jerry Siegel and Joe Shuster)
  13. Speed Saunders Ace Investigator and The Basketball Mystery [26] (by Fred Guardineer)

description:
Don't miss this landmark, extra-sized issue! Following the shocking events of "War Games," Batman faces an entirely different, and dangerous, Gotham City. And with Killer Croc and the Mad Hatter on the loose, does the Dark Knight even stand a chance? Plus, a backup story written and illustrated by David Lapham (Stray Bullets) serves as a prelude to the next epic DETECTIVE COMICS storyline, Lapham's "City of Crime!"

Alone at Night

In the Dark (Tales of Gotham)

description:
1. The "Bat-Man" [2] Frenchy Blake's Jewel Gang (originally untitled): A string of jewel robberies baffle the police. Working on information from a stool pigeon, The "Bat-Man" ambushes a pair of thieves on a rooftop as they've just completed a job. After dealing with the robbers, he frames himself for the heist. But why? (by Rob't Kane [& Bill Finger])

  2. Jest A Second... (by Bob Kane)

  3. Rosati Accordion comic-ad

  4. Speed Saunders Ace Investigator and The Dope Ring [28] (by Fred Guardineer)

  5. Buck Marshall, Range Detective [24] Killing by Proxy (by H. Fleming)

  6. Spy [28] Saboteurs Bob Streamer (by Jerry Siegel and Joe Shuster)

  7. The Crimson Avenger [9] The Bagilan Ruby (by Jim Chambers)

  8. Human Cargo (text story by Jack Anthony)

  9. Bruce Nelson [28] The New Orleans Mardi Gras Murder, Part2 (by Tom Hickey)

  10. Doctor Fu Manchu! [Part 12] (by the celebrated English author Sax Rohmer)
  11. Stamp Detective (text article by Phil. Ately)
  12. Cosmo, The Phantom of Disguise [28] The Truxon Hall Fox Hunt (illustrated by Sven Elvn)

  13. Slam Bradley [28] The Whitethorne Inheritance (by Jerry Siegel and Joe Shuster)

description:
1. The "Bat-Man" [3] The Batman Meets Doctor Death - Doctor Karl Hellfern plans to extort money from the wealthy of the world, but realizes that he must first get Batman out of the way. He has his henchmen lay an ambush for Batman, and Batman is shot, but not fatally, and he escapes. Then he comes back for the Doctor! (by Bob Kane [& Gardner Fox])

    The Batman Meets Doctor Death.

    In his study, Doctor Death talks to his servant Jabah on his plan on ruling the world. He knows there is only one thing in his way - Batman. He decides to lure Batman with a personal notice column in the newspaper. Batman has to go to the General Post Office and ask for a letter addressed to John Jones. Bruce is given directions to meet at the Beverly Apartments. Bruce decides to go home and pack Glass Pellets of choking gas. Batman goes to the location only to be ambushed by two of Doctor Death's goons. Batman tackles a statue to knock down the killers. Then he interrogates, he says if they don't tell him he will kill him. Then Jabah comes out and shoots Batman. Batman throws a gas pellet so he can escape. Batman goes to the doctor as Bruce Wayne. Then Doctor Death gives Jabah poison pollen so he can kill John P. Van Smith. Then Bruce saves John Van Smith by covering his mouth so he can't breath in the pollen. Bruce then follows Jabah as Batman and follows him to the hideout of Doctor Death. Batman ambushed Jabah and Doctor Death. Batman chases Doctor Death to his lab. Doctor Death starts a fire and seemingly is killed by it.

  2. Crime Never Pays [7]

  3. The Stamp Detective (text article)

  4. Larry Steele Private Detective [24] The Murder Of Ace Mullins (by Will Ely)

  5. Spy [29] Colonel Walsh and The Coastal Defense Plans (by Jerry Siegel + Mart Bailey)

  6. The Crimson Avenger [10] The McNeal Kidnappers (by Jim Chambers)

  7. A Game For Two (text story by Paul Dean [aka Gardner Fox])

  8. Speed Saunders Ace Investigator and The Perfect Crime [29] (by Fred Guardineer)

  9. Bruce Nelson [29] The New Orleans Mardi Gras Murder, Part 3 (by Tom Hickey)

  10. Cosmo, The Phantom of Disguise [29] The Avenger (illustrated by Sven Elvn)

  11. Slam Bradley [29] Warning! Keep Out of Hawaii (by Jerry Siegel and Joe Shuster)
    First appearance of Golden Age Doctor Death

description:
Bruce is saddled with the responsibility of taking care of a womans twins for several days, but when he accidentally discovers jewels inside one of the twins rattles, the Batman takes over to prove the innocence of a store owner and ex-con charged with the theft of those jewels.

  1. Batman with Robin - The Boy Wonder: The Tyrannical Twins
  2. Slam Bradley: Shoplifter's Holiday
  3. Air Wave: A Talking Doll
  4. The Boners
  5. Desk Job by Tom Neill (text)
  6. Three-Ring Binks
  7. Boy Commandos: Gangway, Tokyo
name: The Tyrannical Twins

description:
1. Batman - Batman vs. The Vampire: Part 1 (originally untitled) - While prowling the streets of New York City, Batman discovers his fiance Julie Madison attempting to kill a man! He intercedes, saving the man, and takes Julie home telling her to tell Bruce Wayne everything. On hearing the story the next day, Bruce takes Julie to a doctor who prescribes a sea voyage. But Bruce isn't convinced that everything is over, and tails Julie's ocean liner, as the Batman! This issue features the first appearance of the Batarang, and the Batgyro (precursor to the batplane).

  2. Crime Never Pays

  3. Policeman!

  4. Killer's Bait. starring Buck Marshal (Range Detective)

  5. Spy. By Jerry Siegel and Mart Bailey

  6. Larry Steele - Private Detective

  7. Newspaper Nightmare by Paul Dean (text)

  8. The Mammoth Mystery - Speed Saunders, by Fred Guardineer

  9. Bruce Nelson

  10. Cosmo, the phantom of disguise

  11. Slam Bradley

description:
1. Batman - Batman vs. The Vampire: part 2 (originally untitled) - Traveling to Hungary to save his fiance, Batman intercepts a horse-drawn carriage driven by one of the villainous Monk's henchmen, only to find Julie and another woman named Dala unconscious inside. Batman has them stay in a hotel room while he stands guard - but strange things occur during the night!

  2. Odds 'n Ends

  3. Spy

  4. Buck Marshall Range Detective - The Last Act

  5. Crime Never Pays

  6. Larry Steele

  7. Vanishing Gems by Paul Dean (text)

  8. Speed Saunders - The Skull-Face Cult

  9. Cosmo, The Phantom of Disguise

  10. Bruce Nelson

  11. Slam Bradley - Undercover as Bellhops

description:
1. Batman - The Batman Wars Against the Dirigible of Doom - Batman fights Carl Kruger, a would-be world conqueror with top scientists, high technology, and an army of followers.

The Batman Wars Against the Dirigible of Doom

The story begins with The Batman and How He Came to Be. Fifteen years before the current story, Thomas Wayne, his wife and their son Bruce were walking home from a movie. They were stuck up by a mugger, Thomas tries to stop him, and he his shot. His wife screams at the mugger then she is shot by him. Bruce witnesses this before his eyes, then days later Bruce swears on the spirits of his parents to avenge their deaths by spending the rest of his life warring on all criminals. Years later Bruce becomes a master scientist, and he trains his body to physical perfection until he can perform amazing athletic feats. Bruce is thinking about what to pick as a disguise. Bruce then quotes:

Criminals are a superstitious cowardly lot. So my disguise must be able to strike terror into their hearts. I must be a creature of the night, black terrible...a...a..

Then a bat flies in the open window. Then Bruce exclaims:

A Bat! That's it! It's an Omen. I shall become a BAT!

In the present, Bruce Wayne is walking down the crowded streets of Manhattan.* A Dirigible pops up shooting red rays knocking down buildings. Bruce then helps people in the wreckage. Bruce goes home reads the newspaper sees that Professor Carl Kruger and he is now working on a new death ray. Batman goes to the home of Carl Kruger. Batman throws a batarang at Kruger but it was stopped by a sheet of thick glass. Then a henchman knocks out Batman. Kruger leaves Batman in his home with a bomb, but Batman escapes. Then Batman goes to interrogate a lieutenant of Kruger. Then Batman follows him in his Batplane. Batman then sees everyone in the hangar so he throws a gas vial, then he enters the hangar. Batman uses his gun to enter the hangar.** Batman blows up the ray machines then he goes for the Dirigible. Kruger then shoots Batman. Then he destroys the body with a death ray machine in front of a guard. Then later the guard turned out to be Bruce Wayne. Then the next day Kruger attacks the city once again. Batman then follows him with the Batplane and flies the Batplane into the dirigible. Batman then throws a gas pellet at Kruger who crashes his plane into the bay.

*Gotham wasn't created yet so the streets Batman patrolled was New York City.

**Batman use to use a gun

  1. Batman
  2. Big Charlie Ruffing / Pop Warner
  3. Spy
  4. Buck Marshall Range Detective - Mine Of Mystery
  5. Larry Steele
  6. Coffee-Colored Diamonds by Frank Thomas (text)
  7. Speed Saunders - The Northwoods Mystery
  8. Cosmo, The Phantom of Disguise
  9. Bruce Nelson
  10. Crime Never Pays
  11. Slam Bradley

description:
Accused of a murder he didn't commit, Batman must find the real culprits!

  1. Batman - Professor Hugo Strange (originally untitled) - While on patrol, The Batman sees a man gunned down in the street. With his dying breath he murmurs, "strange... fog...". The following night, the city experiences a crime wave when an unnaturally thick fog descends upon it. But The Batman thinks he knows who's behind it.

  2. Spy

  3. Buck Marshall Range Detective - Claim Of Satan

  4. Steve Malone District Attorney

  5. Speed Saunders - The Spider

  6. Cosmo, The Phantom of Disguise

  7. A Climax In Opera by Richard Martin (text)

  8. Bruce Nelson

  9. Slam Bradley

Learning of a deadly plot to sink a large steamship, Batman must track down the suspects!

  1. Batman - The Spies (originally untitled) - The Batman gets lost on back roads. When he stops for directions he hears someone screaming in a nearby house. He finds a man being tortured. He incapacitates the torturers and frees the man... and then the troubles really start!

description:
Batman and Robin take on the Green Dragon!

  1. The Horde of the Green Dragon (Batman & Robin) - a spate of millionaire abductions is baffling - until Batman receives a secret message from his old friend Wong, the 'mayor' of Chinatown!
  2. The Chauffeur Spy (Spy)
  3. Cobra on the Loose (Red Logan)
  4. Switch the Switch (Crimson Avenger)
  5. Monthly Book Review
  6. The Case of the Siva Statue (Speed Saunders, Ace Investigator)
  7. Morton Hijacking & Co. (Steve Malone, District Attorney)
  8. Larson's Boy Gets Kidnapped (Cliff Crosby)
  9. White Trap by Fredric Wells
  10. The French Impersonation (Slam Bradley)

description:
When things go awry on set, Batman must save the day!

  1. The Murders of Clayface (Batman & Robin) - Julie Madison gets a supporting role in Argus Pictures' latest horror film, 'Dread Castle', but when the Lorna Dane, the movie's female lead, ends up dead on set, Batman fears for Julie's safety - and everyone connected to the film's a suspect!
  2. Bart Regan, Spy
  3. An American Reporter in London (Red Logan)
  4. Crimson Avenger
  5. The Jewel Robbers (Speed Saunders, Ace Investigator)
  6. Theft at the Fair by Gardner F. Fox (text)
  7. Steve Malone, District Attorney
  8. Cliff Crosby
  9. Slam Bradley

Even though the Joker appears on the cover, he does not appear anywhere else in this comic.

Reprinted in Batman Archives #1 and Batman Chronicles Volume 2.
name: The Murders of Clayface

description:
Batman and Robin visit a small town to help rid them of evil-doers!

  1. Batman - The Case Of The City Of Terror - Bruce Wayne and Dick Grayson decide to take a cross country vacation. But their vacation comes to an abrupt end when they stop at a city that's been completely taken over by organized crime!

  2. Silly Situations

  3. Spy

  4. Red Logan

  5. Theft In The Abbey by Frank Cooper (text)

  6. The Crimson Avenger

  7. Monthly Book Review

  8. Speed Saunders

  9. Larry Steele

  10. Cliff Crosby

  11. Slam Bradley

description:
Batman and Robin enter a strange land of the bizzare.

  1. The Land Behind The Light - Robin and Batman pay a visit to the mysterious Dr. Marko who has discovered the way to travel to the fourth dimension, following the doctor trough the portal the pair find themselves on a Land of Giants where they are made prisoners of the tyrannic Gorl...

  2. Spy - The Immigration Case

  3. The Inevitable Nephew - with Larry Steele, Private Detective

  4. The Crimson Avenger (no title)

  5. Speed Saunders, Ace Investigator (no title)

  6. Death of a Star (2 page text story)

  7. Steve Malone, District Attorney (no title)

  8. Monthly Book Review: The Gold Bug by E. A. Poe

  9. The Isle of Vampires with Young America's Hero, Cliff Crosby

  10. The Kidnapping with Slam Bradley
name: The Land Behind The Light

description:
Batman and Robin must stop robbers plotting to hit the nation's gold reserve!

  1. Batman - The Secret Cavern - When a surveyor discovers a limestone cavern that runs under the nation's gold reserves, gangsters frame his daughter for murder in order to blackmail him into revealing the cave's entrance. Unfortunately for them, Bruce Wayne happens to have a date with the young lady that very evening!

  2. Spy

  3. Larry Steele - The Case Of The Fugitive Killer

  4. Cliff Crosby

  5. Speed Saunders

  6. Steve Malone

  7. G-Man's Revenge by Tim Standish (text)

  8. The Crimson Avenger

  9. Slam Bradley

This is the first issue of Detective Comics to refer to Gotham City by name.
name: The Secret Cavern

description:
Clayface returns!

  1. Batman - Clayface Walks Again (Batman & Robin : 2nd Clayface story in Detective Comics) -- On a stormy night, Basil Karlo is transferred from prison to the state asylum when the prison ambulance runs off the road. Karlo escapes in the ensuing wreck, free once again to wreak his vengeance on those he believes wronged him!
  2. Bart Regan, Spy --
  3. The Echo (Crimson Avenger) --
  4. Facts --
  5. The Case of the Streamlined Train (Larry Steele, Private Detective) --
  6. Rex --
  7. Speed Saunders, Ace Investigator --
  8. Cliff Crosby Smashes the Loan Shark Racket --
  9. Letter Perfect by Gardner Fox (text)
  10. Steve Malone, District Attorney -
  11. Slam Bradley

description:
CASE OF THE COSTUME-CLAD KILLERS. Batman and Robin set out to clash with a clever gang that steals the uniforms and equipment of police and firemen to commit crimes. But Batman has already identified the person behind this as someone who would relish the humor of the situation: The Joker!

Contents

  1. Batman - Case Of The Costume-Clad Killers
  2. Laffs
  3. Spy
  4. Cliff Crosby
  5. Chief Hot Foot
  6. The Crimson Avenger - Murder on the Airwaves
  7. Silly Willy
  8. Good Books Worth Reading
  9. Larry Steele - The Case of the Tell Tale Candle
  10. Gags
  11. Air Wave - The Case of the Missing Evidence
  12. The Trick by Norman Goss (text)
  13. Slam Bradley

First Appearance of Air Wave!

description:
THE THREE RACKETEERS. Three former racketeers sit around a table in prison, playing cards and discussing how the Batman and Robin brought their dreams of easy wealth to disastrous ends.

The Three Racketeers starring Batman, Robin, and "Crafty" Cal Clate, script by Bill Finger, pencils by Bob Kane, inks by Jerry Robinson and George Roussos. Spy story, art by Louis Cazeneuve. Crime Stalks the Barnyard! starring Cliff Crosby, pencils by Pierce Rice, inks by Arturo Cazeneuve. The Beggars Rebellion starring The Crimson Avenger, script and pencils by Jack Lehti, inks by Charles Paris. The Seal starring Larry Steele, Private Detective, art by Cliff Young. Air Wave story, pencils by Harris Levy (as Lee Harris), inks by Charles Paris. Slam Bradley story, art by Howard Sherman.

Batman - The Three Racketeers

Spy

Cliff Crosby

Good Books Worth Reading

Crimson Avenger

Larry Steele

Ghost Copper by Norman Goss (text)

Air Wave

Slam Bradley

description:
A GENTLEMAN IN GOTHAM! Charged with stealing jewels in a foreign dictator's land, Michael Baffle is supposedly shot and killed. But he cheats death and makes his way to America, the land of the free, and Baffle wonders just how free this land's wealth really is. Batman and Robin have other ideas.

description:
THE JOKER WALKS THE LAST MILE. Depressed because he cannot freely move about and spend the stolen wealth he has in his possession, the Joker decides to just turn himself in!

Batman and Robin in "The Joker Walks the Last Mile"

-On the Run from the Law, Joker decides to turn himself in. Tried and convicted, the clown prince of crime pays the ultimate penalty death by electrocution. After being fried on the Electric Chair, Joker's thugs arrive with a serum that revives him. Using the double jeopardy clause, Joker now finds himself with a clean slate.

Smiles

The Boy Commandos in "The Commandos are Coming"

Crimson Avenger "The Adventure of the Wild Men"

Spy "Murder in the Monument"

Questionable Character by Edgar Weston (text)

Air Wave "The Mystery of His Master's Voice"

Good Books Worth Reading

Slam Bradley "The Mystery of the Unfortunate Teddy Bear"

description:
THE COP WHO HATED BATMAN. Batman and Robin join Commissioner Gordon on a trip to a northern state to watch the state troopers in action. While there, Batman meets a cop who holds a grudge against the Caped Crusader because he believes Batman shot his father in the back years ago.

Contents

  • Good Books Worth Reading
  • Batman and Robin in "The Cop Who Hated the Batman"
  • The Boy Commandos "Nostradamus Predicts"
  • Clancy The Cop
  • The Crimson Avenger in "The Red Letter Day Crimes"
  • Spy "The Case of the Man Who Sold Death"
  • No More Ghosts by John Hilton (text)
  • Air Wave in "The Machine Man"
  • Private Pete
  • Slam Bradley "Mystery of the Priceless Pooch"

description:
CRIMES EARLY BIRD. The Penguin uses birds sold in his store in a variety of ways to commit crimes, but Batman and Robin catch on to his tricks and decide to fight fire with fire.

Contents

  1. Good Books Worth Reading
  2. Batman with Robin - The Boy Wonder - : Crime's Early Bird!
  3. Don & Nancy
  4. The Boy Commandos: Escape To Disaster!
  5. Gags
  6. Smart Sam
  7. The Crimson Avenger: Crime On The Half-Moon!
  8. Comics Zoo
  9. Spy: The Secret Ten.
  10. A Matter of Law by Dalton Weeks (text)
  11. Air Wave: The Case of The Country Crooner!
  12. Chief Hot Foot
  13. Slam Bradley: Case of The Whistling Tooth

description:
(Continued from Detective Comics #66) With the silver dollar standing on edge between the floorboards Two-Face cannot decide between turning himself in or shooting the Batman. So he scoops up the coin, knowing that fate would provide him an answer, and still refusing to take action.. Suddenly a police officer comes through the door and shoots Two Face. He springs back to life and knocks the Batman and the police officer for a loop and escapes. Two-Face's silver dollar coin that was placed in his breast pocket blocked the bullet, saving his life.

Soon Two-Face kidnaps millionaire Henry Logan demanding 200,000 dollars. The Batman and Robin along with the Commissioner Gordon find out that Two Face really kidnapped his 's double. Harvey Kent was entrusted with the knowledge of the double. So everyone realizes Two-Face has the double. Batman and Robin disguise themselves as and his wife to deliver the money. When they arrive at an old ram-shackled barn, Two-Face realizes right away that doesn't have a wife as the Batman and Robin explode onto the scene. A fight ensues. Soon Robin is covered in an "avalanche of hay". Two-Face tries to escape by motorcycle only to have the Batman stop him. Two-Face strikes the Batman rendering him unconscious.

But amid all the criminal endeavors, Two-Face longs to reunite with his fiancee, Gilda, and have a normal life. Days later, a seemingly-healed, seemingly-sane Harvey Kent shows up at her doorstep, and the two share candlelight dinner where she pleads for him to turn himself in, and he asks if she'd be willing to wait for him. Before she can answer, the candle heat melts the wax makeup Kent used, revealing his true scars and true self. Disappointed at his deceit, Gilda fears that Kent actually enjoys being wicked, and before he can explain, Batman breaks in and struggles with Two-Face. Feeling betrayed by Gilda, Kent escapes once again and burns down the Masks and Makeup storefront where he bought the wax mask. With his father now penniless, the shopkeeper's son uses makeup to help Batman and Robin bring Two-Face to justice.

The Batman and Robin soon put on a baseball benefit and raise over 50,000 dollars. Two-Face and his boys come to the stadium to steal the fund raisers money only to be defeated by the Batman and Robin.

description:
CRIME A DAY! After Batman calls The Joker a fool for leaving clues behind to his crimes, the Clown Prince of Crime decides to embarrass him by leaving even more clues behind! Plus, A BREAK FOR SANTA!

Contents

  1. Good Books Worth Reading
  2. Batman with Robin - The Boy Wonder: Crime A Day!
  3. Private Pete
  4. The Boy Commandos: A Break for Santa
  5. Dizzy Data
  6. The Crimson Avenger: The Unlucky Reporter
  7. Spy: Death of The Diamond!
  8. Murder on the Campus by Jack Watson (text)
  9. Air Wave: The Voice from Nowhere.
  10. Chief Hot Foot
  11. Slam Bradley: Case of The Missing Crin!

  9. Slam Bradley: The Histrionic Hoodlums!

description:
TWEEDLEDUM AND TWEEDLEDEE. Batman and Robin are faced with the dual problem of two rather rotund adversaries who set traps and wait for their victims to walk into them.

Batman And Robin Encounter Double Trouble When They Wrestle With Those Fantastic Rotund Rogues "Tweedledum And Tweedledee"!

Contents

  1. Good Books Worth Reading
  2. Batman with Robin - The Boy Wonder: Tweedledum and Tweedledee!
  3. The Boy Commandos: The Trial of Captain Carter
  4. Gags

  6. Private Pete
  7. Spy: The Treachery at the Waterfront
  8. Man About Town by Cleve Jerome (text)
  9. Air Wave: Man Who Avoided Metal!
  10. Slam Bradley: The Adventure of the Wooded Indians!

description:
SLAY EM WITH FLOWERS! After taking over ownership of a flower shop, the Joker and his men use the pretty posies to perpetrate crimes against the wealthy!

Contents

  1. Batman with Robin - The Boy Wonder: Slay 'em with Flowers
  2. The Boy Commandos: The Invasion of America
  3. The Crimson Avenger: The Case of the Lollipop Crimes
  4. Spy: Decks of Doom!
  5. Air Wave: The Man Who Talks His Crimes!
  6. Mountain Invasion by Dan Wallace (text)
  7. Slam Bradley: The Bashful Bandits!

description:
THE CRIME CLINIC. A brilliant surgeon, intrigued by the excitement of crime, opens the Crime Clinic, where criminals who are worried sick over how to commit crimes can go for advice.

  1. Batman with Robin - The Boy Wonder: The Crime Clinic!

  1. Batman with Robin - The Boy Wonder: Quarterback of Crime!

  4. Spy: Peril on Pier 76!
  5. Air Wave: Rogues Along the River!
  6. Cheater's Payment by Tom Neill
  7. The Boy Commandos: The Romance of Rip Carter

description:
Endeavoring to lose some weight, Alfred goes on an exercise program at an out-of-the-way place in the country. While he is gone, the Caped Crusaders face an evil doctor, who uses a certain potion that allows him to control peoples actions, and in the end, they are saved by a mysterious thin man who knows their secret identities.

Chapter Titles

  1. Batman with Robin - The Boy Wonder: Accidentally on Purpose!
  2. Slam Bradley: Vanishing Needles!
  3. The Crimson Avenger: Eighth Column!
  4. Spy: The Message of the Moccasins!
  5. Air Wave: Runaway Plane!
  6. The Boy Commandos: The Triumph of Cholly the Chimp

description:
The Dynamic Duo must stop Ivan Krafft, who has developed a school, under the cover of a gentlemans sporting club, to train criminals on successful crime techniques and then send them out on lucrative criminal endeavors.

Story Titles

  1. Books For Your Christmas List
  2. Batman with Robin - The Boy Wonder: Artists in Villainy.
  3. Laffs / Gags
  4. Air Wave: Bandits on the Beam!
  5. The Crimson Avenger: Scoundrels in Society!
  6. Birds of a Feather by Tod Lowry (text)
  7. Slam Bradley: Shorty Falls in Love
  8. Three-Ring Binks
  9. The Boy Commandos: Never Say Die!
  10. Captain Tootsie and the Secret Weapon!

Four members of a famed card club become the targets for the Clown Prince of Crime, but Batman and Robin discover that The Joker didnt commit the crimes, and they attempt to track down the real culprit.

  2. Batman with Robin - The Boy Wonder: The Joker's Double
  3. Three-Ring Binks
  4. The Crimson Avenger: The Lone Wolf's Number!
  5. Slam Bradley: The Performed Diamonds!
  6. Air Wave: The Short Wave of Crime!
  7. The Saboteur by Eric Carter (text)
  8. The Boy Commandos: Curtain Call for Action

description:
When Alfred hears a radio report that Robin has been captured by a gang of thieves, he decides to use his detective prowess to track the Boy Wonder down and rescue him...even though Bruce Wayne has warned him never to go out on a case alone.

Story Titles

  1. Batman with Robin - The Boy Wonder: Danger Strikes Three!
  2. The Advantures of "R. C." and Quikie: The Cave's Secret
  3. Air Wave: Mr. Smith Gets the Birds!
  4. In Paper There Is Power!
  5. Crimson Avenger: School for Scoops!
  6. Slam Bradley: General Lee Comes to Town!
  7. Such A Nice Man by Eric Carter (text)
  8. Three-Ring Binks
  9. The Boy Commandos: Log of a Lifeboat!
name: Danger Strikes Three!

description:
Bruce and Dick disguise themselves as umbrella repairmen in order to get the Penguin to surface, but when he does, he has a surprise in store for the Dynamic Duo. He then buys an umbrella shop and does his own repairs, placing radio devices into umbrellas in order to direct his men on jobs.

Story Titles

  1. Batman with Robin - The Boy Wonder: The Man of A Thousand Umbrellas
  2. Batman - In Paper there is Power (war propaganda)
  3. Air Wave: Professor Long Sells Air Wave Short
  4. Three-Ring Binks: Blazin' Brody the Fire Eater
  5. Crimson Avenger: Smugglers' Song
  6. Slam Bradley: Tuition Free
  7. Happy Goes Lucky by Art Watkins (text)
  8. Boy Commandos: King Brooklyn the Foist
name: The Man of A Thousand Umbrellas

description:
Bruce and Dick go undercover to get the goods on a loan shark who gladly makes loans to people down on their luck. But the loans have huge interest rates attached to them, and if the borrower refuses to pay those rates, they are eliminated.

Story Titles

  1. Batman with Robin - The Boy Wonder: The Merchants of Misery
  2. Shorty
  3. Air Wave: Underworld Jam Session!
  4. Three Ring Binks
  5. The Crimson Avenger: The Impostor of Newspaper Row!
  6. Slam Bradley: Futures for Sale!
  7. Somebody Plenty Smart by Alan Cabot (text)
  8. Boy Commandos: Battle of Wales!
name: The Merchants of Misery!

description:
The theft of a secret typewriter, valueless except to the inventor, leads Batman and Robin to discover the true identity of the Cavalier.

Story List

Batman - Laboratory Loot

Three-Ring Binks

Air Wave - Man or Mouser

The Crimson Avenger - The Disappearing Desperados!

Private Pete

No Time For Stealing by Tex Palmer (text)

Slam Bradley - Borrowed Brains!

The Boy Commandos - Joyride a la Russe!
name: The Cavalier of Crime

description:
The Caped Crusaders see a connection between the arrival of a showboat and a series of crimes that occur while the ship is docked.

  1. Batman with Robin - The Boy Wonder: Crime Between the Acts
  2. Rollin Stone
  3. Boy Commandos: Commando Performance
  4. Three-Ring Binks
  5. Molly
  6. The Warpath by Devon Taylor (text)
  7. Air Wave: Battle of the Fans
  8. Slam Bradley: The Double Steal
  9. Gus Gaggs
name: Crime Between the Acts

description:
While in prison, The Joker becomes the butt of practical jokes, so he threatens to escape and steal an entire city in retaliation.

  1. Batman with Robin - The Boy Wonder: The Case of the Practical Joker
  2. Casey the Cop
  3. Slam Bradley: The Chicken and the Yegg
  4. Air Wave: Loot for Laughter
  5. Jerry the Jitterbug
  6. Money in the Bank by Stan Carter (text)
  7. Three-Ring Binks
  8. Boy Commandos: Retreat to Paradise

description:
A group of crooks, led by Brainy Bulow, are down on their luck and worried that they cant make a dishonest dollar. Then they notice a Wanted poster and decide to go into an honest business for once: rounding up wanted felons and cashing in on their rewards!

  1. Batman with Robin - The Boy Wonder: Crime's Manhunt
  2. Air Wave: The Hard-Working Hoodlum
  3. Slam Bradley: Case of the Smoking Sign
  4. Nobody Knew by Eddie Bell (text)
  5. Three-Ring Binks: Blow-by-Blow Brody
  6. Boy Commandos: Saga of the Northland

description:
A group of con men take over operations at a county fair and begin bilking people. Then they spot George Barrows, an ex-crook and escaped convict, whom they attempt to blackmail.

  1. Batman with Robin - The Boy Wonder: No One Must Know
  2. Three-Ring Binks: Rusty Boltz the Human Pin-Cushion
  3. Slam Bradley: The Clue of the Cat's Pajamas
  4. Prison Break by Jesse Merlan (text)
  5. Air Wave: The Ride of the Valkyries
  6. The Boy Commandos: The Secret of Hill 118
name: No One Must Know

description:
After Batman helps the police round up a group of notorious crime czars, a new criminal rescues them and organizes them into a new underworld organization, which is designed to efficiently loot all of America!

  1. Batman with Robin - The Boy Wonder: The Blaze
  2. Three-Ring Binks: Hercules Hotcha
  3. Slam Bradley: Marvelous Marbles
  4. Handy Andy (text)
  5. Public Enemy No. 1 by Jesse Merlan
  6. Air Wave: The Phoney Phantoms
  7. Boy Commandos: The Ghost of Kelvin's Keep

description:
Alfred asks for a month off, during which time he goes to another town and opens a detective agency. His first client: Stoney Peters, a criminal who has just shot the Batman!

  1. Batman with Robin - The Boy Wonder: Alfred, Private Detective
  2. Slam Bradley: Bargains in Burglary
  3. Air Wave: Crime Goes into Mourning
  4. Three-Ring Binks
  5. Present From The General by Stan Carter (text)
  6. Boy Commandos: The Sinister League

description:
The Batman tracks down an unusual safe that holds the loot taken years before by the Slashers mob. With the Slasher supposedly dead, the villain has left behind a note leading the Caped Crusaders to the safe, which has seven switches, only one of which opens the door...the rest are connected to a bomb!

  1. Batman with Robin - The Boy Wonder: The Secret of the Switch
  2. Slam Bradley: Call of Death
  3. Gags, Groans N Giggles
  4. Too Much For Granted by Eddie Bell (text)
  5. Three-Ring Binks: Fido the Gabber
  6. Air Wave: Doubling in Danger
  7. Billy Brand
  8. Boy Commandos: He Swings Through the Air
name: The Secret of the Switch

description:
Batman and Robin go undercover to locate crooks responsible for robbing the home of Casper Thurbridge, and trail them to Paradise Jungle, a home for hobos, where they discover Thurbridge himself!

  1. Batman with Robin - The Boy Wonder: The King of the Hoboes!
  2. Slam Bradley: Audacious Alibi
  3. Three-Ring Binks: Millimetre-Gun Murphy
  4. Air Wave: Sound Effects by Air Wave
  5. A Slide For Life by Alton Black (text)
  6. Scruffy the Tramp
  7. Boy Commandos: The Trial of Field Marshall Von Augen
name: The King of the Hoboes!

description:
The Penguin, operating out of a hideout he considers foolproof, police-proof and Batman-proof, concocts a scheme in which he freezes a person, then sends the box with the body to relatives in exchange for the payment of a certain sum of money to safely have them restored to life.

-Batman and Robin "The Temporary Murders"

-The Penguin attempts to extort thousands of dollars from Gotham City's elite by freezing people and the selling the secret of thawing them out. With the help of Alfred, Batman and Robin put an end to the Penguins evil plan.

Slam Bradley in "Veteran in Villainy"

Three-Ring Binks in "Swangaelic the Hypnotist"

Billy Brand

The Refugees by Stan Carter

The Boners

Boy Commandos in "The Locusts of Lohan"

Air Wave "Caution ... Handle without Care"
name: The Temporary Murders

When Wayne Motor Company goes bankrupt because the companys treasurer absconds with its money, Bruce finds himself broke. That predicament creates many headaches for the Dynamic Duo!

  1. Batman with Robin - The Boy Wonder: The Batman Goes Broke
  2. Slam Bradley: Adventure in the Park
  3. Air Wave: Polly Wants a Prize
  4. Home To Roost by Blair Bolton (text)
  5. Three-Ring Binks
  6. Daffy & Doodle
  7. Boy Commandos: Foxhole Chaplain

description:
While visiting the local library, Bruce and Dick witness an attempt to kill a police inspector who, years before, had brought a criminal to justice who escaped and swore revenge on him.

  1. Batman with Robin - The Boy Wonder: The Phantom of the Library
  2. Three-Ring Binks
  3. Slam Bradley: The Legal Pickpockets
  4. Clay Pigeons by Blair Bolton (text)
  5. Shorty
  6. Daffy & Doodle
  7. Air Wave: No Miracles for Muggs
  8. Boy Commandos: Meet the Commandos from Nippon

description:
The Dynamic Duo must put a stop to the clever schemes of Scorpio, a man who plays on the greed of rich men who are superstitious.

The Dynamic duo look to put an end to the sinister schemes of Scorpio.

Operating out of a castle in the mountains beyond Gotham City limits, Scorpio is a mysterious figure whose knowledge of science and the black arts is said to create miracles but it seems every investment banker that encounters Scorpio ends up bankrupt. Batman and Robin confront Scorpio and discover that he uses hypnotism to convince bankers that he has the secret of alchemy. Batman attempts to put and end to Scorpio's grift, but is overwhelmed and imprisoned in Scorpio's dungeon. The caped crusader manages to escape and expose the confidence man for the petty gang leader that he really is.

Batman and Robin star in "The Mountains of the Moon."

Air Wave stars in "Calling Dr. Air Wave"

Three-Ring Binks

Daffy & Doodle

Night Pickup by Ted Loury (text)

Casey The Cop

Slam Bradley starts in "The Playhouse Plunder"

The Boy Commandos star in "The Weird Statues"

description:
When a brave schoolteacher and a community of miners stand up for their rights and safer working conditions against a greedy mine owner, they are met with violence. But having just arrived in town, Batman and Robin play their hazardous and heroic part in bringing justice to Coaltown, U.S.A.

Batman - Coaltown, U.S.A.

Air Wave - The Unlucky Treasure Hunters

Slam Bradley - Turnabout Tactics!

Soft Touch by Al Martin (text)

Three-Ring Binks

Scuffy The Tramp

Boy Commandos - Reconversion For Rats

description:
CRIME ON THE HALF-SHELL! Batman and Robin confront a gang of sea pirates who are stealing oysters from the fishermen in Gotham City! Plus, Slam Bradley takes care of business in THE EDUCATED PIG and WHEN COMRADES MEET featuring the Boy Commandos!

Batman - Crime on the Half-Shell

Air Wave - The Radio Robbers

Gabby

Slam Bradley - The Educated Pig

Dinny

The Little Corporal

Number Up by V.V. Dredaine (text)

Boy Commandos - When Comrades Meet!

description:
1. ACROSTIC OF CRIME! Batman races against the clock to save the life of The Boy Wonder, Robin who has been captured by the Joker!
  2. THE NIGHT OWLS MUSICALE! (Air Wave)
  3. SOMETHING IN THE AIR! Slam and Shorty are on the case, as a gang of jewelry store robbers use kites to get their stolen loot out of store windows! Plus,
  4. SHORTY
  5. JASPER
  6. THE LETHAL LIGHT (2-page text story by V. V. Dredaine)
  7. DAFFY & DOODLE
  8. JOURNEY TO NOWHERE! (The Boy Commandoes)

description:
1. THE MAN WHO LIVED IN A GLASS HOUSE. Batman and Robin defend a home from crooks. But this isnt just any home, its made entirely of glass!
  2. DEAD MEN CAN TELL TALES. Air Wave discovers that the mother of a close friend is getting scammed by a crooked medium.
  3. MOLAR MOBSTERS. Slam Bradley and Shorty go up against a gang using stolen laughing gas to rob their victims!
  4. THREE RING BINKS
  5. DAFFY & DOODLE
  6. "A GAME OF CHECKERS" 2-page text story by Randolph Allen
  7. "BROOKLYN WANTS A KINGDOM" Boy Commandos

description:

description:
1. FOWL PLAY. (Batman) Breaking out of jail once more, the Penguin becomes the assistant to reclusive ornithologist Professor Boyd. Can Batman and Robin track the Penguin down without falling for one of his traps?
  2. SHORTY GROWS UP (Slam Bradley)
  3. "CAPTAIN TOOTSIE SAVES THE SALEPLAIN"
  4. "SAFECRACKERS BY PROXY" (Air Wave)
  5. Prof. Pipp
  6. Jerry The Jitterbug
  7. "TUNE OF DEATH" (full-text story by Stan Carter)
  8. The Rascals
  9. THE FIGHT BEFORE CHRISTMAS. (Boy Commandoes)

description:
THE CRIMES OF TWO-FACE. Featuring the first appearance of Harvey Dent, a.k.a. Two-Face!

At a criminal trial, D.A. Harvey Dent is disfigured by acid thrown into his face, and the shock drives him to become a master criminal who bases all of his crimes on the number two!

  • "The Adventure of the Shooting Spooks!" written by Murray Boltinoff, penciled and inked by Lee Harris. Reprinted in Superman #245.
  • D.A. Harvey Kent (later to be changed to Harvey Dent) starts his case The State vs. "Boss" . The Batman taking the stand stating that shot Bookie Benton and got away. begins shouting that the Batman's lying . The D.A. then shows his proof' a 2 headed silver dollar with 's finger prints found at the crime scene. angered throws acid at the D.A. Despite the Batman's effort to deflect it, the acid disfigures half of the D.A.'s face.
  • Dealing with rejection from people including his fiance, Harvey quickly loses patience waiting for his plastic surgeon. He takes the double headed silver dollar scars one side . He decides to flip the coin to decide his fate.If it lands on the clean side he will wait for the plastic surgeon if the scarred side comes up he will turn to a life of crime. The scarred side lands up.
  • After committing a couple crimes, the coin then decides that they should rob twenty grand from the bond messenger from the Acme Bus Co. The Batman and Robin stop the crime and battle Two-face on a double-decker bus . A bullet meant for Robin ricochets and hits the bus driver. The bus out of control throws the Batman from it.The Robin manages to remove the driver from his seat and stop the bus .
  • Batman and Robin soon discover Two-face's next plan to rob the Bijou Theater from a clue found on one of Two-faces thugs and confront him there.The Batman then chases him from the theater to his hideout. The Two-face gets the drop on the Batman holding him at gunpoint. He flips the coin to decide whether to kill the Batman but it lands on its edge on a crack between the floorboards. Two-face remains unable to kill the Batman staring at the coin in the floorboard at issues end. Continued in Detective Comics #68.
  • Air wave witnesses the murder of his boss, it is committed by men disguised as spooks, they escape, and Air wave end up being the prime suspect of the murder.

Contents

  1. Good Books Worth Reading
  2. Batman with Robin - The Boy Wonder - : The Crimes of Two-Face!
  3. Don & Nancy Magicians Entertaining Their Friends!
  4. The Boy Commandos: The Sphinx Speaks
  5. Jerry The Jitterbug
  6. Laffs
  7. The Crimson Avenger: Murder Will Out
  8. Spy: Little Discs of Death
  9. Flaming Bullets by Eric Carter (text)
  10. Air Wave: The Adventure of The Shooting Spooks
  11. Sport with the Sports
  12. Slam Bradley: Case of The Dripping Drum

1. COMMISSIONER GORDON WALKS A BEAT! Batman and Robin are summoned to the GCPD headquarters where they learn that Commissioner Gordon has been replaced by orders of the mayor. Gordon has been demoted to a beat cop and Batman's deputy status is also revoked without explanation!

  4. "THE PINK SHEET" (full-text story by Dalton Warren)

description:
ON COVER: Batman watches as Catwoman strikes Robin, tearing the shoulder of his costume and leaving scratch marks.

  1. THE BLACK CAT CRIMES! (Batman) Catwoman escapes from prison and threatens three wealthy men with old superstitions about black cats! Plus,
  2. Chief Hot Foot: Humor strip
  3. THE CRAZY CUSTOMERS! (Slam Bradley) Slam and Shorty witness some mighty strange purchasing habits inside a department store and decide to investigate!
  4. Captain Tootsie's Counter-spook: Tootsie Roll add
  5. "THE UNCANDID CAMERA!" (Air Wave) an escaped con tries to use fake backgrounds in photos to make the police think he has fled to Europe but Air Wave figures it out.
  6. "THE TALKING CAT" (text story by Mal Terret)
  7. "FOUR SWORDS FOR A KING" (Boy Commandoes) a "magic scientist" summons the commandoes back thru time to become the basis for the three Musketeers.

description:
on the cover: a masked thug coming up from a manhole, points a tommy gun at Batman but is distracted as Robin rolls the manhole cover at him.

  1. THE DAWN PATROL CRIMES (Batman) A cunning masked criminal known as the Shiner, hatches a scheme to transport stolen radium into Canada using the pilots of the Dawn Patrol. Batman and Robin are alerted to the crime and end up in an aerial battle with the Shiner and his gang.
  2. SOUTH OF THE BORDER (Slam Bradley) Slam and Shorty follow a gang of jewel thieves across the border into Mexico.
  3. "TALENT HUNT" (text story by Max Olin)
  4. HEROES FOR A DAY The Boy Commandos take a vacation at a spring camp.
  5. "The voice of Spooky Sommers" Air Wave tales on a crooked loan company.
  6. Casey the Cop
name: The Dawn Patrol Crimes

description:
1. THE CRIME PARADE (Batman) The Joker begins a new wave of robberies based on the most requested song of the day on the radio! The Joker uses titles of requested songs on the radio for his newest crime spree. Will Batman and Robin be able to set the score before Joker gets to his Crescendo? Or will Joker beat them?
  2. "THE CRIME EXPRESS" (Air Wave)
  3. "CAPTAIN TOOTSIE AND THE RADAR RESCUE"
  4. HONEST WILLIE: (humor strip)
  5. "KNOCK OUT" (text story by Stan Carter)
  6. Chief Hot Foot: (humor strip)
  7. SHORTY OF THE ROYAL MOUNTED Slam and Shorty take a trip to Canada
  8. ASSIGNMENT IN LONDON. the Boy Commandos are asked to perform in a movie in

deck: Batman and Robin star in "The Citadel of Crime"
description:
1. THE CITADEL OF CRIME! (Batman and Robin ) When recently released criminal Dan Briggs crawls into a small desert town dying from a gunshot wound, Batman decides to investigate the rash of disappearing ex-cons. Disguised as convict Tom Lorne, Batman winds up working in a factory at the Citadel of Crime for the arch-criminal The Thinker. In an effort to arm the underworld, The Thinker had been using indentured ex-cons to build tanks, flame throwers, bazookas, and other military-grade weaponry. Batman procures one of the tanks and uses it to liberate the enslaved ex-cons, who revolt. In the chaos that ensues, The Thinker accidentally electrocutes himself. After the dust settles the ex-cons continue working at the plant but for honest purposes, and the Citadel of Crime becomes the Citadel of Honest Ex-Criminals.
  2. "PROSECUTOR BY PROXY" (Air Wave)
  3. "FIREMAN, SAVE MY CHILD" (Slam Bradley)
  4. "SAFETY IN NUMBERS" (text story by Patric Dobbs)
  5. "WHEN HITLER CAME BACK" (The Boy Commandos) A German actor tries to revive the SS by playing on the rumor that Hitler is still alive. The Boy Commandos discover the farce and are quick to put an end to the second coming of the Third Reich.
name: The Citadel of Crime

description:
1. CASE OF THE SILENT SONGBIRDS! Batman and Robin investigate the Penguins activities, as he has started a bird-lovers club in which the members are all singers. Penguin demands large sums of money from the members of the club, and when they refuse to pay, he attacks them and steals their voices!
  2. THE PERILOUS PUPPETS (Slam Bradley)
  4. TUBBY THE HAPPY TRAMP
  5. FELONS IN FUR (Air Wave)
  6. CHIEF HOT FOOT
  7. "BLACKBOARD OF DEATH" (text story by Rex Drake)
  8. SHORTY
  9. "D-DAY ON THE BOULDER" (Boy Commandos)
name: Case of the Silent Songbirds

description:
1. PIGMIES IN GIANTLAND. A crazed scientist called Dr. Agar tries to convince wealthy people that he has created a shrinking gas capable of reducing anything to one-fifth of its normal size. How will Batman and Robin defeat this new foe when they themselves are captured and shrunk?!
  2. MODERN PAUL REVERE (Slam Bradly)
  3. ROGUES AND RED HOTS (Air Wave)
  4. "SHORTY THE FIGHT FAN"
  5. "NOTHING TO LOSE" (text story by Tex Blane)
  6. DAFFY & DOODLE
  7. "NEVER-SAY-DIE LAND" (Boy Commandoes)
name: Pigmies in Giantland

description:
1. CRIME IN REVERSE! (Batman) The Joker is at it again! Batman and Robin are at their wits end when Joker starts to commit crimes in reverse!
  2. "THE BANDITS AND THE BELLS" (Air Wave) when a crook called Limpy is "saved by the bell" twice he decides to make bells a part of all his crimes.
  3. "SHORTY THE MEDICINE MAN" (Slam Bradly) Slam and shorty follow a crook on to a ship and get knocked out, waking up at see.
  4. "FIREMAN FOR A DAY" (text story by Cliff Rhodes)
  5. THREE-RING BINKS
  6. "RIP CARTER - - KILLER" (Boy commandoes)
name: Crimes in Reverse

description:
1. THE ISLE OF YESTERDAY Batman and Robin track some criminals from Gotham City to an island called Goodwinville, where the people still live as they did in the 1890s!
  2. "CRIME SPOTS ON THE SUN" (Air Wave)
  3. "THE HEAT'S ON" (Slam Bradly)
  4. NIFTY
  5. "LONG CHANCE" (text story by Kit Martin)
  6. "THE QUARTERBACK FROM BROOKLYN" (The Boy Commandos)
name: The Isle of Yesterday

description:

  3. "POLLY WANTS TO CRACK A SAFE" (Air Wave)
  4. "LOCAL COLOR" (text story by Tom Neill)
  5. JERRY THE JITTERBUG

description:
1. THE BOX Batman and Robin follow the trail of several criminals who want to obtain a mysterious box; the strange thing is that everyone who obtains this box is murdered shortly after!
  2. "STATIC SEES DOUBLE" (Air Wave)
  3. "THE MAN WHO DROWNED NINE TIMES" (Slam Bradly)
  4. THE SPOOKS
  5. CASEY THE COP
  6. "THE COWARD" (text story by Ted Fields)
  7. CHIEF HOT FOOT
  8. "FIFTY BELOW ZERO" (The Boy Commandoes)
name: The Box

description:
1. THE HUMAN KEY! (Batman) A master locksmith poses as a criminal in order to help Batman and Robin capture a notorious criminal and his gang!
  2. "SOCIETY PLUNDERS" (Slam Bradly)
  3. "SKATES FOR SCOUNDRELS" (Air Wave) A gang is using innocent kids trying to run a skate delivery business to move money from a bank robbery.
  4. THREE RING BINKS
  5. "STOLEN CACHE" (text story by Robert Hale)
  6. "THE UNWELCOME SANTA CLOUSE" (Boy Commandoes)
name: The Human Key

description:
1. "THE DEAD MAN'S CHEST" (Batman) after recognizing his own handwriting on a treasure map Bruce has Professor Nichols send him and Dick back in time to a pirate ship in 1667.
  2. "THE CITY OF GLASS" (Air Wave) Air Wave fights criminals in an exhibit city made entirely of glass.
  3. "TRUTH + PENALTY = CRIME-CATCHERS" (Slam Bradly)
  4. "TOO MANY COOKS" (text story by Cliff Rhodes)
  5. "A TALE OF TWO BROOKLYNS" (Boy Commandoes)

description:
1. "THE INVISIBLE CRIMES" (Batman) the Joker steals an elixir that makes him invisible.
  2. "THE INSIDE STORY OF THE ROBOTMAN" (Robotman) after Robotman gets broken into pieces it's up to the police to figure out how to put him back together. summoned scientists are baffled until one finds instructions in his leg.
  3. "SHORTY MEETS THE CHAMP" (Slam Bradly)
  4. SHORTY
  5. "SECRET CODES CAN BE FUN" (text story by HenryLysing)
  6. "THE MYSTERY OF THE MARY CELESTE 2" (Boy Commandoes)
  7. DAFFY & DOODLE

1. "THE CRIMES OF JADE" (Batman) when a shipment of Wyoming Jade is stolen Batman and Robin work alongside a Chinatown detective to solve the case.

  6. OZZIE

  8. ARIZONA RANGER
  9. "DR. Z, FUTURE CRIMINAL" (Boy Commandoes)
